The '''K9 Thunder''' ({{Korean|hangul=K-9 자주곡사포|hanja=K-9 自走曲射砲|rr=K-9 Jajugoksapo}}) is a South Korean [[155 mm]] [[self-propelled howitzer]] designed and developed by the [[Agency for Defense Development]] and private corporations including [[Hanwha Techwin|Samsung Aerospace Industries]], [[Hyundai WIA|Kia Heavy Industry]], Dongmyeong Heavy Industries, and [[Poongsan Corporation]] for the [[Republic of Korea Armed Forces]], and is now manufactured by [[Hanwha Aerospace]].<ref name="Hanwha Defense K9">{{cite web |url=https://www.hanwha-defense.co.kr/kor/products/firearms-system-k9.do |title=Hanwha Defense K9 Self-propelled Howitzer |publisher=Hanwha Defense |access-date=29 January 2020 |archive-date=17 July 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210717092526/https://www.hanwha-defense.co.kr/kor/products/firearms-system-k9.do |url-status=dead }}</ref> K9 howitzers operate in groups with the [[K10 ammunition resupply vehicle]] variant.<ref name="JoongAng K9A2"/><ref name="news2day.co.kr">{{Cite web |script-title=ko:한화그룹, 대우조선해양 인수로 국내 유일 육·해·공 전문 방산기업으로 '우뚝' |url=https://www.news2day.co.kr/article/20220926500126 |access-date=2022-09-28 |website=뉴스투데이 |language=ko}}</ref>

The entire K9 fleet operated by the ROK Armed Forces is now undergoing upgrades to '''K9A1''', and a further upgrade variant '''K9A2''' is being tested for production. As of 2022, the K9 series commands a 52% share of the global self-propelled howitzer market—including wheeled variants—for all systems delivered since 2000.<ref name="JoongAng K9A2">{{cite web|url=https://www.joongang.co.kr/article/25053184#home|script-title=ko:8년전 우크라 때리자 꽂혔다...세계최강 K9자주포 진화 이유 [김민석 배틀그라운드]|publisher=[[JoongAng Ilbo]]|date=6 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220307121130/https://www.joongang.co.kr/article/25053184#home|archive-date=7 March 2022|access-date=7 March 2022|author=Kim Minseok}}</ref><ref name="news2day.co.kr"/>

==Development==
In the 1980s, the ROK Armed Forces embarked on the development of a new artillery system to contest North Korean equipment. The armed forces operated [[M107 self-propelled gun]]s and [[M109 howitzer#K55|K55 self-propelled howitzers]]. However, they had shorter firing ranges compared to [[Koksan (artillery)|M-1978 Koksan]] and were outnumbered by various North Korean artillery. With the success in designing and manufacturing the [[KH178 105 mm towed howitzer|KH178 105 mm]] and [[KH179 155 mm towed howitzer]]s, and experience gained by license producing the K55 (KM109A2), the Ministry of Defense ordered the development of a new system that would have a longer firing range, faster firing rate, and high mobility. The development started in 1989 and was led by the [[Agency for Defense Development]] (ADD) and [[Hanwha Aerospace|Samsung Aerospace Industries]] (now Hanwha Aerospace).<ref name="K9 Developer Interview (1)">{{cite AV media |date=2015-09-16 |script-title=ko:[첨단국가의 초석, 방위산업] 자주포의 새 차원을 열다 – K-9 천둥(1부) |language=ko |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F2tivketAK0  |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211222/F2tivketAK0 |archive-date=2021-12-22 |url-status=live|publisher=국방TV}}{{cbignore}}</ref>

Since 1983, the ADD researchers had been collecting and analyzing data for future artillery. They saw that burst fire and quick relocation would become the dominant factor in artillery battles and built an automatic loading system for testing in 1984. In 1987, the ADD offered an upgrade plan to the existing K55 inspired by the United States' M109 Howitzer Improvement Program (standardized in 1990 as [[M109 howitzer#M109A6 Paladin|M109A6]]), but was rejected by the [[Republic of Korea Army]] in 1988. As a result, and at the beginning of K9 development, the ADD was determined to create a new weapon system and worked on a conceptual model until 1991. Early concepts requested by the military included river crossing capability and the installation of [[M61 Vulcan]] as an anti-air weapon, which were later removed due to being unnecessary for such a long-range weapon.<ref name="K9 Developer Interview (1)" /><ref>{{Cite web  |title=[K9 5회] 세계적 추세 '화포 자동화 방안' 연구 |url=https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220223/2/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |access-date=2022-06-05 |website=[[Kookbang Ilbo]] |archive-date=4 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230404154135/https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220223/2/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |url-status=dead }}</ref>

In 1989, the only design data the researchers could obtain at that time were the provisions of the four-nation ballistic agreements, namely the United States, the United Kingdom, Germany, and Italy, to secure the homogeneity of the ammunitions—the new 52 caliber gun fires a NATO standard ammunition (L15A1) at a speed of 945 m per second from chamber volume of 3,556&nbsp;cm<sup>3</sup>. The first domestic design was prepared by extending and modifying the 155&nbsp;mm 39 caliber gun used for the KH179.<ref>{{Cite web  |title=[K9 9회] 핵심 '무장' 개발 처음부터 난관 |url=https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220307/1/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |access-date=2022-06-05 |website=[[Kookbang Ilbo]] |archive-date=4 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230404145553/https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220307/1/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |url-status=dead }}</ref> The first firing test was held in January 1992 but experienced many problems due to design errors.<ref>{{Cite web  |title=[K9 10회] 위험 도사린 무장 사격시험 |url=https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220307/2/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |access-date=2022-06-05 |website=[[Kookbang Ilbo]] |archive-date=13 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221213061917/https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220307/2/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |url-status=dead }}</ref>

In September 1990, a Korean developer visited the United Kingdom in search of turret design technology which was known to have been developed by British [[Vickers Shipbuilding and Engineering|Vickers]] for [[AS-90]]. Vickers refused the technology transfer. Instead, the company offered the AS-90 for sale. The developer also visited [[Marconi Electronic Systems|Marconi]], but the negotiations ended with an unsatisfactory result due to a high requested price. Therefore, developers pursued a domestic electrohydraulic driving system, using the experience in turret design and turret driving devices of the [[K1 88-Tank|K1 MBT]]. The simulator was built in 1991.<ref name="국방일보">{{Cite web  |title=[K9 12회] 회전시키는 포를 1mil 이내로 위치시켜라 |url=https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220322/3/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |access-date=2022-06-05 |website=[[Kookbang Ilbo]] |archive-date=4 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230404152623/https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220322/3/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name="K9 Developer Interview (3)"/>

The next year, researchers found that the disproportionate moment of the 52-caliber was twice of the K55. The balancing machine, which increased the capacity of the existing hydraulic balancing machine, did not sufficiently compensate for the imbalance moment value due to the change in the position of the armament. The driving force was very different depending on the driving angle. The same problem appeared in Germany's [[Panzerhaubitze 2000]], which was under development. A joint research team from the ADD and [[Seoul National University of Science and Technology]] calculated an accurate theoretical model, and concluded that adjustment to system configuration was possible without major design changes.<ref name="국방일보"/><ref name="K9 Developer Interview (3)"/>

Meanwhile, loud noise from hydraulic generators, which can cause hearing loss under long exposure, was also a problem. The engineers of the ADD and Dongmyeong Heavy Industries (now Mottrol) found that the noise was due to excessive shaking of hydraulic pressure, thus creating an experimental device using the principle of Helmholtz attenuators used in car mufflers. The noisy equipment became quieter and the hydraulic pulsation was significantly reduced. Overall, the domestic design showed driving precision of less than 1 mil in the standard error range.<ref name="국방일보"/><ref name="K9 Developer Interview (3)">{{cite AV media |date=2015-10-15 |script-title=ko:[첨단국가의 초석, 방위산업] 자주포의 새 차원을 열다 – K-9 천둥(3부) |language=ko |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yXvZZ9eowMs  |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211222/yXvZZ9eowMs |archive-date=2021-12-22 |url-status=live|publisher=국방TV}}{{cbignore}}</ref>

In the winter of 1991, the ADD held talks with engineers from Samsung Aerospace Industries' special research institute. The ADD originally demanded that Samsung be in charge of system assembly only, as the company had no experience in developing its own tracked vehicle design despite having the experience in manufacturing K55 under license. The decision was overturned and the manufacture of the MTR (Mobility Test Rig) was decided upon.<ref>{{Cite web  |title=[K9 13회] 신자포 체계개발과 차량개발의 분리 의견 나오자.... |url=https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220418/1/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |access-date=2022-06-05 |website=[[Kookbang Ilbo]] |archive-date=4 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230404145554/https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220418/1/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |url-status=dead }}</ref> Samsung worked with [[KAIST]] on suspension and [[Seoul National University]] & [[Pohang University of Science and Technology]] on mobility systems. The engine was co-developed with American [[AAI Corporation]]. The test of the MTR was finished in November 1992.<ref>{{Cite web  |title=[K9 16회] 기동실험차량 제작해 기동설계요소 확보 |url=https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220420/2/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |access-date=2022-06-05 |website=[[Kookbang Ilbo]] |archive-date=4 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230404145555/https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220420/2/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |url-status=dead }}</ref>

In April 1992, BMY Combat Systems (now BAE Systems Land and Armaments) invited members of the ADD for its first M109A6 Paladin release ceremony and expressed interest in participating in Korea's self-propelled howitzer program by upgrading the K55 to Paladin standard. In May, members of BMY Combat Systems and Teledyne Brown visited the ADD, and suggested co-development of a new howitzer based on the P-52, a 52-caliber Paladin variant. This proposal was rejected by Korean developers. Later, during a Data Exchange Agreement meeting, South Korea and the United States confirmed that the U.S. had no claim to any intellectual property rights of the howitzer, to avoid possible disputes in the future.<ref name="K9 Developer Interview (2)">{{cite AV media |date=2015-10-15 |script-title=ko:[첨단국가의 초석, 방위산업] 자주포의 새 차원을 열다 – K-9 천둥(2부) |language=ko |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Lh_CVAm3XNo  |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211222/Lh_CVAm3XNo |archive-date=2021-12-22 |url-status=live|publisher=국방TV}}{{cbignore}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web  |title=[K9 14회] "우리 자주포 우리가 개발한다"며 미측 제안 거부 |url=https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220418/2/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |access-date=2022-06-05 |website=[[Kookbang Ilbo]] |archive-date=4 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230404151106/https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220418/2/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |url-status=dead }}</ref>

From 1992 to 1993, the developers explored and confirmed the required operational capability, such as the system suitability of major components and the possibility of reaching the maximum firing range of {{convert|40|km|mi|sp=us}}. An internal review predicted that the howitzer would achieve a localization rate of 107 out of 235 (45.5%) technologies by the late 1990s. Unsatisfied with the review, South Korea decided to continue developing main system, main gun, 155&nbsp;mm ammunition, fire control system, structure, and autoloader; meanwhile, the engine, transmission, and INS (inertial navigation system) were to be imported from foreign partners, and license produce hydropneumatic suspension to target 70% localization rate. The engineers faced the biggest challenges designing main gun and suspension due to lack of experience. While licensing the K55, its main gun was brought as a finished product and the suspension was produced from knowledge from the United States.<ref name="K9 Developer Interview (2)" /><ref>{{Cite web  |title=[K9 8회] 적용가능 기술 45.5% 불과....국산화율 70%로 설정 |url=https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220303/1/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |access-date=2022-06-05 |website=[[Kookbang Ilbo]] |archive-date=4 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230404145609/https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220303/1/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |url-status=dead }}</ref>

Based on a review of the required operational capability in October 1992, a firing rate of three shots within 15 seconds was chosen for economic feasibility. The rationale was that it is difficult for targets to be out of fatal range within 15 seconds after the first impact, and that the firing rate can be shortened depending on training level. If a firing rate of three shots in 10 seconds was demanded, it would have caused a huge increase in development costs as well as an unnecessary burden on researchers.<ref>{{Cite web  |title=[K9 15회] 신자포 개발 형태, 업체 주도로 전환할 수 있을까 |url=https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220420/1/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |access-date=2022-06-05 |website=[[Kookbang Ilbo]] |archive-date=4 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230404151101/https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220420/1/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |url-status=dead }}</ref>

The development was delayed between March and August 1993 as a result of purge of [[Hanahoe]], a private military club within the [[Republic of Korea Armed Forces]], who aligned with military dictator [[Chun Doo-hwan]], by president [[Kim Young-sam]] who was elected by democratic election. In addition, the army logistics department also refused to sign the letter of agreement for XK9 until a development plan for the maintenance elements is created.<ref>{{Cite web  |title=[K9 17회] 신자포, 하천 장애물을 극복해야 한다지만.... |url=https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220420/6/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |access-date=2022-06-05 |website=[[Kookbang Ilbo]] |archive-date=4 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230404145552/https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220420/6/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |url-status=dead }}</ref> When the [[Joint Chiefs of Staff]] finalized the system development agreement in late August 1993, the Defense Ministry approved a prototype development plan in September and the president approved the project in early October.<ref>{{Cite web  |title=[K9 18회] 모델명, 90년대 기필코 전력화 의지 담아 '9' 선택 |url=https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220425/1/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |access-date=2022-06-05 |website=[[Kookbang Ilbo]] |archive-date=4 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230404152619/https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220425/1/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |url-status=dead }}</ref>

Since domestically developed armor steel plates were applied for the first time, the researchers decided to produce and compare armor plates from both imported and domestic materials to reduce the risk. Meantime, Samsung began to train and employ master craftsman welders whose skills were verified by the U.S. Aberdeen Test Center. Armor plates went through a series of tests such as stress and ballistic impacts, and researchers verified that the domestic plate performed better than the imported plate.<ref>{{Cite web  |title=[K9 19회] 탁월한 장갑판재 용접실력...방호력 우수 |url=https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220429/1/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |access-date=2022-06-05 |website=[[Kookbang Ilbo]] |archive-date=13 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221213061917/https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220429/1/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |url-status=dead }}</ref>

The ADD saw that the HSU (Hydropneumatic Suspension Unit) provides better mobility and crew comfort. At that time, the HSU caused problems with some equipment and it was yet to be fully verified for durability, igniting controversy internationally. Therefore, it was inevitable to introduce and localize a British Air-Log (now Horstman) HSU that is used for the AS-90. However, when researchers applied the Air-Log HSU on the MTR and prototypes, they soon found that the HSU couldn't support heavier vehicles, thus failing the durability test. Since May 1997, engineers from the ADD and Dongmyeong Heavy Industries have spent a year on five redesigns and 11 durability tests. After the development of the new HSU, the design was exported back to Britain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizhankook.com/bk/article/16344|script-title=ko:[단독] K-9 자주포, 영국 수출길 오르나|publisher=Biz Hankook|date=4 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220616154049/http://www.bizhankook.com/bk/article/16344|archive-date=16 June 2022|access-date=16 June 2022|author=Kim Daeyeong}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220503/1/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do|title=[K9 20회] HSU 개발 '땅팔 일 없고 사격도 빠르고 정확히|publisher=kookbang|date=3 May 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220616154049/http://www.bizhankook.com/bk/article/16344|archive-date=16 June 2022|access-date=16 June 2022|author=Shin Inho}}</ref>

Developers changed the power pack for the MTR with the combination of an 850&nbsp;hp engine from [[Detroit Diesel]], which offered a smaller cooling system, and [[Allison Transmission]]'s X1100 automatic transmission. This powertrain passed the tests on the MTR, but the engine failed on prototype vehicles due to low durability. The researchers looked for new engines from overseas. [[Perkins Engines]] and [[MTU Friedrichshafen]] showed interest in selling engines in August 1995. Perkins Engines offered the CV12 Condor, which was also used in the [[Challenger 2]], but detuned to 1,000&nbsp;hp. The price was slightly higher than that of Detroit Diesel; it was a relatively large 12-cylinder, which would require a design change on the chassis and there was a technical insufficiency of cooling devices. MTU's MT-881, though more expensive, offered a compact eight-cylinder with the same cutting-edge cooling system from the latest Euro Pack. The engine was also used for the PzH 2000 in Germany, and was undergoing trials in Germany and Canada. After examinations, the German design was chosen for the program, and was tested on an ATR (Automotive Test Rig) for a year starting in September 1997.<ref>{{Cite web  |title=[K9 23회] 우여곡절 끝 獨 MTU 엔진 장착 |url=https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220516/1/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |access-date=2022-06-06 |website=[[Kookbang Ilbo]] |archive-date=4 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230404145634/https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220516/1/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |url-status=dead }}</ref>

In the spring of 1992, the test gun experienced a detonator breakage caused by a differential pressure, at which the pressure increases in the opposite direction of the shell. After many years of failures and updates, researchers decided to change the shape of the propellant in 1997. The tiny pellets of the U.S.-style propellant, which have seven holes similar to briquettes, were replaced with 19 holes by mimicking the German style without knowing the specification. After numerous tests, the gun achieved a range of {{convert|40|km|mi|sp=us}} below 53,000 psi in 1998.<ref>{{Cite web  |title=[K9 24회] 新자주포 포탄 독자개발 성공 |url=https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220516/3/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |access-date=2022-06-11 |website=[[Kookbang Ilbo]] |archive-date=4 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230404151104/https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220516/3/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |url-status=dead }}</ref>

A total of three prototypes were built and performed their first open trials in 1996. During the test, the prototypes succeeded in firing at distances of {{convert|40|km|mi|sp=us}} and six rounds per minute, but failed to fire three rounds in 15 seconds.<ref>{{Cite web  |title=[K9 28회] 신자포 공개시범사격....급속사격은 못했지만··· |url=https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220602/1/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |access-date=2022-06-16 |website=[[Kookbang Ilbo]] |archive-date=4 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230404145615/https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220602/1/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web  |title=[K9 29회] ROC 수정... 전투중량 2톤 증가 |url=https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220607/1/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |access-date=2022-06-16 |website=[[Kookbang Ilbo]] |archive-date=4 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230404154140/https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220607/1/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |url-status=dead }}</ref> In December 1997, one of the prototypes was damaged by fire, due to failing complete combustion, after testing 18 rounds in three minutes. One researcher was killed and two injured. The damaged prototype's internal system survived the fire, and was repaired for further use. The prototypes fired 4,100 rounds and underwent {{convert|13800|km|mi|sp=us}} of mobility tests including extreme temperature conditions and various type of terrain such as ski courses during the winter season.<ref name="salesperson interview" /><ref name="K9 Developer Interview (3)" /><ref>{{Cite web  |title=[K9 30회] 안타까운 사고...개발 성공으로 승화 |url=https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220607/3/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |access-date=2022-06-16 |website=[[Kookbang Ilbo]] |archive-date=4 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230404145606/https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220607/3/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |url-status=dead }}</ref>

After firing 12,000 rounds and driving {{convert|18000|km|mi|sp=us}} over 10 years, the development was finished in October 1998 with the achievement of an 87% localization rate.{{notetag|Korean standard for localization rate of military equipment is based on the money value of product.}}<ref name="ROK Defense Media Agency">{{cite web |date=2015-08-10 |script-title=ko:군인의 물건 군수품 돋보기 <15> K9 자주포와 K10 탄약운반차 |language=ko |url=https://demaclub.tistory.com/2743 |publisher=Republic of Korea Armed Forces Defense Media Agency}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|reason=See reliable sources list on [[WP:KO/RS]]|date=March 2025}} The contract for the Batch I of K9 artillery system was awarded to Samsung Aerospace Industries in December 1998.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=101&oid=001&aid=0004342744 |script-title=ko:삼성항공, 국방부와 신형 자주포 공급계약 | publisher=[[Yonhap News Agency]] |date=1998-12-22}}</ref> The produced vehicles were supposed to be delivered to the [[Republic of Korea Army]]. However, a [[Battle of Yeonpyeong (1999)|1999 naval battle between the two Koreas]] caused the delivery to be rerouted to the [[Republic of Korea Marine Corps]]. The first vehicle was rolled out in December 1999, and was given to the marines in [[Yeonpyeongdo]].<ref>{{cite web |date=2016-01-03 |title=[e-무기]34세 연구원의 희생 딛고 탄생한 'K-9 자주포' |language=ko |url=https://www.edaily.co.kr/news/read?newsId=01134886612514112&mediaCodeNo=257 |publisher=[[Edaily]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=102&oid=001&aid=0004503459 |script-title=ko:국방부, 155mm 신형자주포 배치 |publisher=[[Yonhap News Agency]] |date=1999-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web  |title=[K9 31회] K9이 제때 완성되지 못했다면? |url=https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220607/4/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |access-date=2022-06-16 |website=[[Kookbang Ilbo]] |archive-date=4 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230404145602/https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220607/4/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |url-status=dead }}</ref>

==General characteristics==
The K9 is of welded construction, using {{convert|20000|kg|lb|sp=us}} of MIL-12560H armor steel developed by [[POSCO]] for [[K2 Black Panther]] project,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsroom.posco.com/kr/%ED%8F%AC%EC%8A%A4%EC%BD%94%EC%97%90%EB%8F%84-bts%EA%B0%80-%EC%9E%88%EB%8B%A4/|script-title=ko:포스코에도 BTS가 있다|publisher=[[POSCO]]|date=23 July 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220417004833/https://newsroom.posco.com/kr/%ED%8F%AC%EC%8A%A4%EC%BD%94%EC%97%90%EB%8F%84-bts%EA%B0%80-%EC%9E%88%EB%8B%A4/|archive-date=17 April 2022|access-date=17 April 2022|author=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.subcomsolutions.com/assets/pdf/POSCO-Armour-Plates.pdf|title=POSCO Armour Plates|publisher=Subcom Solution|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220417011756/https://www.subcomsolutions.com/assets/pdf/POSCO-Armour-Plates.pdf|archive-date=17 April 2022|access-date=17 April 2022|author=}}</ref> which can withstand explosion pressure and fragments from 152&nbsp;mm HE rounds, armor piercing rounds, and anti-personnel mines all around. The vehicle can protect crews from [[CBRN defense|CBRN threats]] using an air-purification system.<ref name="Hanwha Defense K9" />

The power-pack consists of a {{convert|1000|hp|kW|sp=us}} MT881Ka-500 MTU Friedrichshafen engine licensed by Ssangyong Heavy Industries (now STX Engine)<ref>{{cite web |title=STX Engine |url=http://www.stxengine.co.kr/kor/html/biz/military/army_03.aspx |website=STX ENGINE |language=Korean}}</ref> and an Allison Transmission X1100-5A3 transmission licensed by Tongil Precision Machinery Industries (now [[SNT Dynamics]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hisntd.com/kor/product/defense/mobile.html |title=SNT Dynamics}}</ref> and is installed on a [[hydropneumatic suspension]] chassis. Driven by Firstec driving system,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firsteccom.co.kr/ |title=Firstec |publisher=Firstec}}</ref> the {{convert|47|t|sp=us}} vehicle has maximum speed of {{convert|67|km/h|mph|sp=us}} or maintains above 56&nbsp;km/h at 60% longitudinal slope, and is capable of operating in various terrain conditions including desert, snow, jungle, and mountains. It can also be deployed as self-propelled [[coastal artillery]] for surface targets, creating a no-access zone within  its firing range.<ref name="JoongAng K9A2" /><ref>{{Citation |script-title=ko:세계 최고 수준의 명품 자주포! [국군무기도감 시즌2:K9 자주포] | date=29 December 2019 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=c9bX3NJlk4M |access-date=2023-09-05 |language=en}}</ref>

The main armament is a CN98 [[155&nbsp;mm]], 52-calibre artillery gun manufactured by Kia Heavy Industry (now [[Hyundai WIA]]),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hyundai-wia.com/business/defense_ground_01.asp |title=Hyundai WIA |publisher=Hyundai WIA}}</ref> with a maximum firing range of {{convert|41|km|mi|sp=us}} with K307 rounds. Or {{convert|54|km|mi|sp=us}} with K315 rounds fired from the upgraded K9A1 variant. The CN98 is rated 1,000 EFC (equivalent full charge) with continuous firing under severe condition.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Kim |first=Jae-Kab |date=2006 |title=An Study on the Erosion Characteristics of Tube CN98 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/264016832 |website=ResearchGate}}</ref> The K9 stores 32 rounds in the bustle rack (16 rounds in each row), while an additional 16 rounds are stored at the rear of the hull (8 rounds on each side). Assisted by a semi-automatic feeding system, fire control system, and the Battalion Tactical Command System (BTCS), the vehicle can burst fire three rounds in 15 seconds and has the ability of [[multiple rounds simultaneous impact]] (MRSI) mode.<ref>{{Cite web |title= Finnish Army article on K9 Thunder |url=https://maavoimat.fi/en/self-propelled-howitzer-k9-thunder |access-date=2025-01-02}}</ref> It has a maximum rate of fire of six to eight rpm for three minutes (until emptying ammunitions store in the bustle), then reduced to two to three rpm for sustain fire (hand carrying ammunitions to feeder). The vehicle can [[shoot-and-scoot]] and be ready to fire in 30 seconds between stops or 60 seconds between maneuvers. After firing, it can relocate to a new position in 30 seconds to increase survivability from enemy counter-battery attacks.<ref name="Hanwha Defense K9" />

[[File:A live fire exercise of the K9 battery of the ROK Army.webm|thumb|thumbtime=1:42|A live fire exercise of the K9 battery of the [[Republic of Korea Army|ROK Army]]]]

The shells, fed by from a [[K10 ammunition resupply vehicle]], enter from the door behind the turret and are automatically rolled and loaded on the rack. When the shooting specification is decided, the chosen shell is placed on the tray in the center of the rack. A loader pulls the tray handle, and the shell slides into the carrier. Then the carrier repositions to the angle of shooting, and transfers the shell to the autoloader, which immediately "throws" the shell into the barrel.<ref>{{Cite web  |title=[K9 21회] 포탄 이송·장전을 자동화...탄약 취급 안전 보장 |url=https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220510/1/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |access-date=2022-06-06 |website=[[Kookbang Ilbo]] |archive-date=4 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230404145559/https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220510/1/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |url-status=dead }}</ref>

The K9 uses the TALIN (Tactical Advanced Land Inertial Navigator) 5000 for its INS, purchased from [[Honeywell Aerospace]] after the announcement of the development of a [[ring laser gyroscope]] system that can withstand the shock from gunfire. The positioning device consists of a ring laser gyro that can detect up to one-ten-thousandth of Earth's rotational angular velocity, an accelerometer that can detect up to one-hundred-thousandth of Earth's gravitational acceleration, and a navigation computer that calculates using data detected by these sensors. This positioning device calculates the location of the self-propelled gun, the azimuth angle of the gun to the north, and the elevation and inclination angle of the earth's horizontal plane by itself. The calculated navigation information and posture information are provided to the fire control system, which has a positional accuracy within 10 m, an azimuthal accuracy within 0.7 mil, and an elevation and inclination angle accuracy within 0.35 mil.<ref>{{Cite web  |title=[K9 11회] 화포 자동화와 링 레이저 자이로 |url=https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220322/1/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |access-date=2022-06-05 |website=[[Kookbang Ilbo]] |archive-date=4 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230404145610/https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220322/1/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |url-status=dead }}</ref>

The K9 has both manual (mechanical and optical) and automatic (electronic) fire control system. The manual fire control system is similar to that of K55, while the AFCS consists largely of a system controller, display, a shooting controller with a built-in ballistic program, a communication processor, and a power controller, and serves as an interface between the operator and the machine. Various electronic control devices such as positioning devices, gun & turret driving systems, ammunition transports, trigger devices, gun temperature sensors, and radios are interlinked to achieve automation. The AFCS uses ballistic programs and muzzle velocity sensors to calculate firing data on its own, as well as to receive shooting commands via data and voice communication from the BTCS. The FCS is the first of its kind in that it can calculate weather measurements by altitude, thus providing more precise shooting specifications.<ref>{{Cite web  |title=[K9 25회] 탄도·사격통제 독자개발 ... 완전 국산화 |url=https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220523/1/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |access-date=2022-06-11 |website=[[Kookbang Ilbo]] |archive-date=13 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221213061917/https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220523/1/BBSMSTR_000000100185/view.do |url-status=dead }}</ref>

==Further developments==

===Ammunitions===

==== Extended range munitions ====
In October 2013, the DAPA announced a future plan for K9 upgrades along with a new extended range ammunition starting in 2014.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.korea.kr/news/pressReleaseView.do?newsId=155921643 |script-title=ko:제71회 방위사업추진위원회 개최결과 |publisher=Republic of Korea |date=2013-10-11}}</ref>

In August 2014, Hanwha and [[Poongsan Corporation|Poongsan]] were selected as the preferred bidders for new extended ammunition used for both the K9 and the K55A1. The two companies will compete to win the project.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hankyung.com/politics/article/201408129743i |script-title=ko:사거리연장탄 개발놓고 한화와 풍산 정면대결 |publisher=[[The Korea Economic Daily]] |date=2014-08-12}}</ref>

In July 2019, Hanwha was removed from the new ammunition project due to unsatisfactory results, making Poongsan the sole bidder.<ref>{{cite web|date=2019-07-11|title=(주)한화, 성과 미달로 방위청으로부터 계약 해지 통보 받아|url=http://www.discoverynews.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=107664|access-date=2021-08-31|website=디스커버리뉴스(DISCOVERYNEWS)|language=ko}}</ref>

In November 2020, new extended-range ammunition by Poongsan was accepted for service after years of tests. The new ammunition combines BB (base bleed) with RAP (rocket-assisted propulsion), reaching 54&nbsp;km with HE or 45&nbsp;km with [[Dual-purpose improved conventional munition|DP-ICM]]. The manufacturing will start in 2022, and will be operational by 2023.<ref>{{cite web|date=2020-11-26|script-title=ko:[단독] '최대 54km 타격' K9 자주포 155mm 사거리 연장탄 개발 완료|url=http://www.bizhankook.com/bk/article/21026|access-date=2021-08-31|website=비즈한국|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|script-title=ko:탄탄한 기술력이 일군 탄약 국산화 이제 세계가 배운다|url=https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20210423/3/BBSMSTR_000000100147/view.do|access-date=2021-09-02|website=[[Kookbang Ilbo]]|archive-date=4 April 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230404154149/https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20210423/3/BBSMSTR_000000100147/view.do|url-status=dead}}</ref> However, the introduction was delayed as 5 out of 77 items did not meet the standards during [[heat wave]] and [[cold wave]] tests.<ref>{{Cite web |last=홍 |first=석희 |date=2023-02-20 |script-title=ko:[단독] 무기체계 47%는 자료만 보고 수입했다..."年 수천억대 추가 비용" |url=http://biz.heraldcorp.com/view.php?ud=20230220000080 |access-date=2023-09-01 |website=헤럴드경제 |language=ko}}</ref>

In February 2023, the South Korean military accepted new high performance [[5.56×45mm NATO]] and [[7.62×51mm NATO]] ammunition that increases performance by three times compared to previous models. The new technology can be applied on any projectiles, allowing K9 Thunder to possibly increase the range by three times. The technology is patented in the United States, Russia, the European Union, and other countries.<ref>{{Citation |script-title=ko:[단독] 이번엔 K-총탄‥탱크 뚫는 총알 도입하나? (2023.06.06/뉴스데스크/MBC) | date=6 June 2023 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=thFbWRfXZnE |access-date=2023-08-27 |language=en}}</ref>

In August 2023, Poongsang Corporation announced completion the 60&nbsp;km extended range ammunition development. The new ammunition was expected to enter service in 2024.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-08-29 |script-title=ko:풍산, K방산 기술력 강화...155mm 사거리 연장탄 개발 |url=http://www.snmnews.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=522353 |access-date=2023-09-01 |website=철강금속신문 |language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=K9 계열 자주포 최대 사거리 40km → 60km |url=https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20230830/1/ATCE_CTGR_0010020000/view.do |access-date=2023-09-01 |website=[[Kookbang Ilbo]] |language=ko }}{{Dead link|date=May 2024 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>

On 6 February 2024, the DAPA announced completion of the 54&nbsp;km extended range program. New ammunition, known as LAP, is scheduled for mass production in 2024.<ref>{{Cite web |last=이 |first=종윤 |date=2024-02-06 |title=155㎜ 자주포 사거리연장탄 개발 완료, 40→60㎞로 늘어 |url=https://www.fnnews.com/news/202402061106570222 |access-date=2024-02-07 |website=[[The Financial News]] |language=ko-KR}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=김 |first=준태 |date=2024-02-06 |title=155㎜ 자주포 사거리연장탄 개발 완료…40→60㎞로 늘어 |url=https://www.yna.co.kr/view/AKR20240206030700504 |access-date=2024-02-07 |website=[[Yonhap News Agency]] |language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-02-06 |title=K-9 사거리, 30% 확장…올해부터 LAP탄 양산 돌입 |url=https://www.obsnews.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=1430231 |access-date=2024-02-19 |website=OBS경인TV |language=ko}}</ref>

On 29 May 2025 at MADEX 2025, Poongsan said the 60&nbsp;km range ammunition named "ERM-HE" (Extended Range Munition-High Explosive) has 30&nbsp;m circular error probability (CEP).<ref>{{Cite web |last=최 |first=대성 |date=2025-05-29 |title=[MADEX 2025] LIG넥스원·풍산, 새로운 '도전' 성공할까 |url=https://www.safetimes.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=230604 |website=Safe Times}}</ref>

==== Special munitions ====
Poongsan also has been working on different types of ammunition, such as POM (PARA – Observation Munition) and GGAM (Gliding Guided Artillery Munition) since 2013 and 2014 respectively.<ref>{{cite web|date=2020-04-09|script-title=ko:장사정 활공포탄 / 관측탄 / 상부공격 지능탄|url=http://www.defensetoday.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=743|access-date=2021-09-02|website=디펜스투데이|language=ko}}</ref>

====Foreign compatibility====
In 2010, K9 test fired [[M982 Excalibur]] during Australia's Land 17 artillery replacement program.<ref name="Defense Today K9" />

In May 2016, K9 test fired JBMoU (Joint Ballistics Memorandum of Understanding) compliant HE-ER ammunition in Sweden successfully, reaching 43&nbsp;km in distance.<ref name="Defense Today K9" />

In September 2022, a K9A1 SPH and a K10 ARV demonstrated compatibility with a variety of American munitions in a live-fire test at [[Yuma Proving Ground]] in [[Arizona]]. The howitzer managed to fire 3 rounds in 16 seconds and 6 rounds in 43.3 seconds using [[M795 projectile]]s. K9A1 became the first foreign platform to fire XM1113 RAP munition and achieved 53&nbsp;km in shooting distance at an elevation of 900 mils.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Valpolini |first=Paolo |date=2022-10-07 |title=Hanwha's K9 artillery solutions proven compatible with US munitions |url=https://www.edrmagazine.eu/hanwhas-k9-artillery-solutions-proven-compatible-with-us-munitions |access-date=2022-12-02 |website=EDR Magazine |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-10-16 |title=K9A1 now fires US munitions - three rounds in 16 sec and 50km range |url=https://bulgarianmilitary.com/2022/10/16/k9a1-now-fires-us-munitions-three-rounds-in-16-sec-and-50km-range/ |access-date=2022-12-02 |language=en-US}}</ref><ref name="K9 and K10 with US munitions fire demo">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4cBbAaqOCMo |title=K9 and K10 proven compatibility with US munitions at YPG live-fire demo |date=10 Nov 2022 |publisher=Hanwha Aerospace}}</ref>

In November 2023, Hanwha Aerospace signed a 160 billion KRW export deal with BAE Systems to supply a modular charge system (MCS) for NATO members.<ref>{{Cite web |script-title=ko:한화, NATO 호환 155mm 장약 첫 수출... "英과 전방위 방산협력" |url=https://www.hanwhaaerospace.co.kr/kor/media/newsroom/view.do?seq=369 |access-date=2023-12-05 |website=www.hanwhaaerospace.co.kr |language=ko}}</ref>

In April 2024, Hanwha Aerospace conducted test fires of the M982A1 Excalibur Increment Ib at Yuma Proving Ground in Arizona using Norwegian K9 VIDAR variant. The K9 used various fuze modes and achieved less than one meter circular error probability (CEP) in Point Detonating mode and 5 meters above the target in Height of Burst mode from 50&nbsp;km away.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-08-10 |title=K9 Self-Propelled Howitzer Achieves Milestone with Raytheon M982A1 Excalibur Artillery Projectile |url=https://militaryleak.com/2024/08/10/k9-self-propelled-howitzer-achieves-milestone-with-raytheon-m982a1-excalibur-artillery-projectile/ |access-date=2024-08-29 |website=militaryleak.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-08-07 |title=Hanwha: K9 howitzer successfully tested with Excalibur artillery projectile |url=https://defence-industry.eu/hanwha-k9-howitzer-successfully-tested-with-excalibur-artillery-projectile/ |access-date=2024-08-29 |language=en}}</ref>

===Electronics and sensors===
In 2004, KRCMI (Korea Research Center for Measuring Instruments) developed a [[Doppler radar]] calibration system, which significantly increased accuracy by lowering the impact error from 0.1% to 0.05%.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newsmaker.or.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=68923 |title='2018 계량측정의 날' 동탑산업훈장 수훈 |publisher=NewsMaker |date=2018-12-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.korea.kr/news/pressReleaseView.do?newsId=156301496 |script-title=ko:국민행복과 신뢰의 기반은 정확한 계량측정에서 |publisher=Republic of Korea |date=2018-10-31}}</ref> Using the new technology, the ADD and DST (Davit System Technology) launched a joint project for a domestic MVRS (muzzle velocity radar system). In September 2007, DST announced the development of model MVRS-3000, increasing both performance and localization of the vehicle.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fnnews.com/news/200709182223484626?t=y |script-title=ko:포구속도측정기 국산화 성공 |publisher=[[The Financial News]] |date=2007-09-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://dst.co.kr/html/sub02/sub02_0201.php |title=DST Radar |publisher=DST}}</ref>

In February 2012, the [[Defense Acquisition Program Administration]] (DAPA) launched an arms localization project, which includes the K9's INS.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.mt.co.kr/mtview.php?no=2012020914168224405&outlink=1&ref=https%3A%2F%2F |script-title=ko:방사청 "핵심무기 부품 국산화 실현한다" |publisher=[[Money Today]] |date=2012-02-09}}</ref> In May 2012, Doosan DST was selected for the domestic INS development.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.news1.kr/articles/674030 |script-title=ko:방사청, 핵심부품 국산화 개발에 박차 |publisher=News 1 |date=2021-05-18}}</ref> The plan to install a domestic INS on the K9 was later changed to license production in 2015, while domestic models were to be used for the [[K21]] and the [[K30 Biho|K30]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.naver.com/main/read.naver?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=101&oid=011&aid=0002812667 |script-title=ko:탄약서 자주포.레이더까지...한화 '글로벌 톱10 방산기업' 정조준 |publisher=Seoul Economics |date=2016-03-30}}</ref>

In September 2015, offset trade was signed between [[Honeywell Aerospace]] and Navcours. Under the agreement, Navcours will license production and service of the TALIN 5000 INS, which is already being used in the K9 and K55A1, for domestic use, and supply Honeywell Aerospace as well.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://kr.aving.net/news/view.php?articleId=1277628&Branch_ID=kr&rssid |script-title=ko:하니웰, 넵코어스와 'TALIN관성항법장치' 관련 협력 계약 체결 |publisher=Aving Global Network |date=2015-09-02}}</ref>

===K-AIC===
On 20 June 2024, the Republic of Korea Army and Hanwha Aerospace signed an MOU on cooperation and support for the promotion of the Korea-Army International Course (K-AIC), a Korean weapons system curriculum that will begin in July. The program was created to provide Korean military regular training to nations that have purchased or plan to purchase Korean weapons. Under the agreement, the army will run separate training programs specialized for foreign soldiers twice a year in connection with various military schools, including the [[K2 Black Panther]] tank, the K9 Thunder self-propelled howitzer, and the [[K239 Chunmoo]] MLRS. Participants will also train on equipment and combat operation for four weeks and observe the [[Korea Combat Training Center]] (KCTC) as well as manufacturing plants.<ref>{{Cite web  |script-title=ko:외국군에 국산 무기체계 교육 국제과정 개설 |url=https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20240621/7/ATCE_CTGR_0010030000/view.do |access-date=2024-11-27 |website=[[Kookbang Ilbo]] |language=ko}}</ref><ref name="KAIC2025"/>

Participants are divided into different courses based on the requirements of their home countries and their individual skill levels. They receive intensive, hands-on training that includes courses on K2 Tank Operations, K9 Self-Propelled Howitzer Operations, K2 Tank Maintenance, and K9 Self-Propelled Howitzer Maintenance. By training alongside officers from the Korean military, they have more opportunities to share practical knowledge and foster cooperation. The program is also divided into a basic course for the first half and an advanced course for the second half, allowing for a customized curriculum that fits the specific needs of the participating countries. The training starts with integrated education at Army Headquarters, followed by a systematic study of the K2 tank and K9 self-propelled howitzer, which includes theoretical lessons, simulator exercises, tactical operations, and live-fire and maneuver drills. In the final week, participants visit military units to gain hands-on experience with the actual weapons, improving their real-world combat skills.<ref name="KAIC2025_2">{{cite web|date=2025-07-18|title=2025-2기 육군 국제과정, 역대 최대규모 6개국 70명 외국군 장병 참가|url=https://www.shinailbo.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=2085644|website=신아일보|language=ko}}</ref>

