In 1999, the same year Poland joined  [[NATO]], it launched a military program named Regina Project to replace its 152mm Soviet-era SPGs with the NATO standard 155&nbsp;mm artillery system. The British [[BAE Systems]] was chosen by Poland for technical cooperation to build a new design. Later, the plan was changed to use modified [[AS-90]] turret and combine with UPG-NG chassis from domestic company [[Bumar-Łabędy]] to shorten the development schedule.<ref name="K9 Poland">{{cite news |url=https://nownews.seoul.co.kr/news/newsView.php?id=20141229601024 |script-title=ko:방산(防産)강국 폴란드가 K9 수입한 사연 |publisher=Now News |date=2015-01-19}}</ref>

However, the UPG-NG chassis experienced series of issues during trial. The chassis was unable to support its 20 t turret by failing the shock absorption from 155&nbsp;mm 52 caliber weapon system, often breaking and cracking the parts. In addition, the factory that has been producing S-12U engine for the vehicle was closed down, causing major discrepancy in logistics even before the mass production stage. In 2008, after four years since the prototype was revealed, Polish Ministry of Defense warned Bumar to fix the issue by 2014, otherwise it will look for foreign partner instead. Bumar failed to meet the ROC (required operational capability), thus K9 Thunder platform was chosen for the weapon project.<ref name="K9 Poland" />

In December 2014, Samsung Techwin signed a cooperation agreement with [[Huta Stalowa Wola]] to supply modified K9 Thunder chassis for [[AHS Krab]] self-propelled howitzer. The changes to the chassis (referred to as PK9)<ref>{{Cite web |author=((Defence24)) |date=2017-12-13 |title=Dwa kroki do artyleryjskiej samodzielności |url=https://defence24.pl/przemysl/dwa-kroki-do-artyleryjskiej-samodzielnosci |access-date=2024-12-13 |website=defence24.pl |language=pl}}</ref> include a fire suppression system in the crew compartment, air filtration system, air conditioning and the APU.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2019-03-21 |title=Series Manufactured Krab Howitzers for the Polish Military |url=https://defence24.com/armed-forces/land/series-manufactured-krab-howitzers-for-the-polish-military |access-date=2023-12-22 |website=defence24.com |language=pl}}</ref> The deal is worth $310 million for 120 chassis, which includes related technology transfer and the power pack. From 2015 to 2022, 24 units will be manufactured in South Korea, and 96 will be license produced in Poland.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hankyung.com/politics/article/201412185981i |title=K9 문당 28억원에 폴란드 수출 |publisher=[[The Korea Economic Daily]] |date=2014-12-18}}</ref> First chassis rolled out on 26 June 2015, and all 24 vehicles produced in Korea left for Poland as of October 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.heraldcorp.com/military/view.php?ud=20150626000130 |title=K-9 자주포, 폴란드 수출 차체 1호기 출하 |publisher=[[Herald Corporation]] |date=2015-06-26}}</ref> HSW will begin producing PK9 chassis starting in 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.yna.co.kr/view/AKR20161215168000003?input=1195m |script-title=ko:한화테크윈, 폴란드에 K9 자주포 96대 수출(종합) |publisher=[[Yonhap News Agency]] |date=2016-12-15}}</ref>

On 16 December 2020, 2 guns were added for training school as part of 2016 contract adjustment.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-07-10 |title=Zamówienie na dodatkowe Kraby dla wojska! |url=https://www.hsw.pl/aktualnosci/zamowienie-na-dodatkowe-kraby-dla-wojska/ |access-date=2025-07-11 |website=Huta Stalowa Wola S.A. |language=pl-PL}}</ref>

Late in May 2022, the Polish government donated 18 AHS Krab howitzers to [[Ukraine]] to assist the [[Ukrainian military]] to defend against Russia during the [[2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine|invasion of Ukraine]].<ref name="CharlishHunder2022">{{cite news |last1=Charlish |first1=Alan |last2=Hunder |first2=Max |title=Poland gives 18 howitzers to Ukraine - public radio |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/ukraine-crisis-arms-poland-idUSL1N2XL0AF |access-date=4 June 2022 |work=[[Reuters]] |date=May 29, 2022}}</ref> On 29 May, Polish minister of defense visited South Korea for high level talks regarding the purchase of various Korean weapons including additional K9 chassis to increase AHS Krab production.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2022-05-30 |script-title=ko:한국·폴란드 국방장관 회담... 국산 무기 수출길 열릴까 |url=https://segye.com/view/20220530522949 |access-date=2022-06-10 |website=[[Segye Ilbo]] |language=ko |last1=Com |first1=Segye }}</ref> On June 7, Poland and Ukraine signed a contract for the purchase of an additional 54 units plus support vehicles, in a deal worth US$700 million. The agreement was the largest defense contract that Polish defense industry had made.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Poland Sells Its Krab Howitzers to Ukraine: A Record-Breaking Contract |url=https://defence24.com/industry/poland-sells-its-krab-howitzers-to-ukraine-a-record-breaking-contract |access-date=2022-06-10 |website=defence24.com |date=7 June 2022 |language=pl}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Poland to sell 60 AHS Krab self-propelled howitzers to Ukraine |url=https://www.ukrinform.net/rubric-ato/3497984-poland-to-sell-60-krab-selfpropelled-howitzers-to-ukraine.html |website=[[Ukrinform]] |access-date=4 June 2022 |date=June 2, 2022}}</ref>

On 5 September 2022, Poland ordered 48 Krabs and other support vehicles for a value of PLN 3.8 billion zlotys (USD $797 million).<ref>{{Cite web |date=5 September 2022 |title=Kraby zamówione w Kielcach |url=https://defence24.pl/przemysl/kraby-zamowione-w-kielcach |website=Defence24 |publisher=Defence24 Sp. z o.o. |location=Warsaw, Poland |language=pl |trans-title=Krabs ordered at Kielce |access-date=5 September 2022}}</ref>

On 23 December 2024, the contract worth PLN 9 billion for 96 Krabs, command vehicles, command and staff vehicles, ammunition vehicles, and repair workshops was signed. The delivery schedule for this batch is scheduled by the end of 2029.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-12-23 |title=Kolejne uzbrojenie dla #WojskoPolskie. |url=https://x.com/MON_GOV_PL/status/1871214300351676464 |website=x.com/ |publisher=Ministerstwo Obrony Narodowej}}</ref>

On 8 April 2025, HSW signed a ₩402.6 billion deal with Hanwha Aerospace to supply parts including power packs for 87 AHS Krabs between 2026 and 2028.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-04-08 |title=한화에어로스페이스, 폴란드에 4000억원대 자주포 부품 공급 |url=https://www.hanwhaaerospace.com/kor/media/newsroom/view.do?seq=497 |website=Hanwha Aerospace}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Walkowski |first=Antoni |date=2025-04-07 |title=Koreańskie silniki do Kraba. Porozumienie Hanwha i HSW |url=https://defence24.pl/przemysl/koreanskie-silniki-do-kraba-porozumienie-hanwha-i-hsw |access-date=2025-06-09 |website=defence24.pl |language=pl}}</ref>

====K9PL====
[[File:A Polish K9 howitzer maneuvers on the firing range for a live fire demonstration.jpg|thumb|right|Polish K9 Thunder maneuvers on the firing range for a live fire demonstration in Bemowo Piskie, Poland on March 31, 2023]]
On 27 July 2022, [[Polish Armaments Group]] (PGZ) and Hanwha Defense signed a [[framework agreement]] to supply 672 '''K9PL'''. Hanwha Defense hoped to expand the deal plus adding '''K10 ARV''' and '''K11 FDCV''' support vehicles.<ref name="PGZ">{{cite news|url=https://www.yna.co.kr/view/AKR20220727090752504|script-title=ko:폴란드 "한국에 K2 1천대·FA-50 3개편대·K-9 600문 주문"(종합2보)|publisher=[[Yonhap News Agency]]|date=27 July 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220729001831/https://www.yna.co.kr/view/AKR20220727090752504|archive-date=29 July 2022|access-date=29 July 2022|author=Kim Yeonsuk|newspaper=[[Yonhap News Agency]] }}</ref><ref name="Defence24">{{cite web|url=https://cdn.defence24.pl/2022/07/29/b8a347b7-2dc4-4ddb-82dc-b49174860aa2.pdf|title=Poland Procures Korean MBTs, Aircraft, and Howitzers|publisher=Defence24|date=28 July 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220729165048/https://cdn.defence24.pl/2022/07/29/b8a347b7-2dc4-4ddb-82dc-b49174860aa2.pdf|archive-date=29 July 2022|access-date=29 July 2022|author=Maciej Szopa}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=구 |first=자윤 |date=2022-07-28 |script-title=ko:한화디펜스, 폴란드에 K9·K10·K11 수출 기본 계약 |url=https://www.fnnews.com/news/202207280916238083 |access-date=2022-07-30 |website=[[The Financial News]] |language=ko-KR}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wojsko-polskie.pl/au/articles/aktualnosci/czolgi-haubice-i-samoloty-z-korei-dla-sil-zbrojnych-rp/|title=Czołgi, haubice i samoloty z Korei dla Sił Zbrojnych RP|date=27 July 2022|access-date=31 July 2022}}</ref> Poland will also produce AHS Krab in parallel; however, due to the low production capability, the deliveries of the existing order will be completed by 2026.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-07-26 |title=Polska kupi 1000 czołgów. Błaszczak: planujemy pozyskanie dodatkowych F-35 lub F-15 [WYWIAD] |url=https://defence24.pl/polityka-obronna/polska-kupi-1000-czolgow-blaszczak-planujemy-pozyskanie-dodatkowych-f-35-lub-f-15-wywiad |access-date=2022-07-26 |website=defence24.pl |language=pl}}</ref> On 26 August 2022, an executive contract of $2.4 billion was signed to acquire 212 K9PL manufactured by Hanwha Defense as a Batch I order. Poland took loans equivalent to 70% of the total purchase cost (which includes Polish orders for the [[K2 Black Panther]], K9 Thunder, as well as the [[FA-50]]), from the South Korean banks.<ref>{{Cite web  |date=2023-06-05 |script-title=ko:[단독] "12조 금융 지원 또 달라"...2차 협상 난항 |url=https://news.sbs.co.kr/news/endPage.do?news_id=N1007218207 |access-date=2023-08-26 |website=[[Seoul Broadcasting System]] |language=ko}}</ref> The deal does not include accompanying vehicles; however, it consists of crew training, including simulators, logistics packages, and a large amount of ammunition. To fill up Polish inventory quickly, the first 48 howitzers (upgraded K9 to A1) will come from the Republic of Korea Army inventory, and the ROKA will be compensated with newly produced vehicles later.<ref>{{Cite web |last=홍 |first=의표 |date=2022-09-26 |script-title=ko:[단독] 우리 군이 쓸 전차·자주포도 폴란드로‥'전력 공백' 우려 |url=https://imnews.imbc.com/replay/2022/nwdesk/article/6411448_35744.html |access-date=2022-09-28 |website=[[MBC News]] |language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-09-26 |script-title=ko:육군 갈 K2전차·K9자주포 '폴란드 먼저'... "안보 공백 우려" |url=https://www.news1.kr/articles/4814296 |access-date=2022-09-28 |website=[[News1 (South Korean company)|News1]] |language=ko}}</ref> These secondhand vehicles are sometimes referred to as K9GF (Gap Filler).<ref name="K9GF">{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iXCdpCK8Gxo |title=[K-방산] K9자주포, K2전차 동시 폴란드 수출 선적 현장 포착..전차 180대 자주포 1차 212문, 2차 152문도 이렇게 납품 됩니다 |date=2024-10-31 |last=MBC경남 NEWS |access-date=2024-11-25 |via=YouTube}}</ref> All K9PL, including K9GF, will be equipped with the Polish C2 network system and Topaz Automated Fire Control System, which is intended for operating with Polish command vehicles.<ref>{{Cite web |last=tf.co.kr |date=2022-12-06 |title=K2 '흑표' 전차 ·K9 '썬더' 자주포 두 달 만에 폴란드 도착 |url=http://news.tf.co.kr/read/ptoday/1984344.htm |access-date=2023-05-15 |website=더팩트 |language=ko}}</ref> Under the contract, Hanwha is responsible for delivery of all 212 vehicles by 30 September 2026.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-12-09 |script-title=ko:승승장구 K방산, 폴란드發 변수에 제동걸리나 |url=https://biz.newdaily.co.kr/site/data/html/2022/12/09/2022120900105.html |access-date=2023-05-15 |website=[[Newdaily]] |language=ko}}</ref> Poland plans to build K9PL locally afterward via technology transfer for the Batch II.<ref name="K9A1 Poland">{{Cite web |title=Czołgi, haubice i amunicja za miliardy już w tym roku. Umowy wykonawcze z Koreą podpisane |url=https://defence24.pl/przemysl/czolgi-haubice-i-amunicja-za-miliardy-juz-w-tym-roku-umowy-wykonawcze-z-korea-podpisane |access-date=2022-08-27 |website=defence24.pl |date=26 August 2022 |language=pl}}</ref> On 7 September, Hanwha Defense and WB Electronics signed a $139.5 million deal for installation of Polish communication systems on the Batch I order.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-09-08 |script-title=ko:[단독] 한화디펜스, 폴란드 방산업체와 '1920억원 규모' 통신 시스템 공급계약 체결 |url=http://www.theguru.co.kr/news/article.html?no=41817 |access-date=2022-09-12 |website=www.theguru.co.kr |language=ko}}</ref>

The first 24 K9PL(GF) was rolled out on 19 October 2022.<ref>{{Citation |title=K9PL Roll-Out Ceremony | date=24 October 2022 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vkg5IodHEo4 |language=en |access-date=2022-12-02}}</ref> The delivery ceremony was held in Poland on 6 December.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-12-06 |script-title=ko:폴란드 "한국 기술로 국방력 강화"... K9자주포·K2전차 초도분 도착 |url=https://www.news1.kr/articles/4886796 |access-date=2022-12-06 |website=[[News1 (South Korean company)|News1]] |language=ko}}</ref> The first new K9PL began its construction in July 2023.<ref>{{Cite web  |date=2023-07-14 |script-title=ko:한화 김동관 폴란드行...한국선 K9 자주포 조립 개시 |url=https://news.mt.co.kr/mtview.php?no=2023071413022870403 |access-date=2023-08-26 |website=[[Money Today]] |language=ko}}</ref>

On 1 December 2023, Poland and Hanwha Aerospace signed a $2.6 billion agreement for 6 Batch I K9PLs by 2025, 146 Batch II K9PLs between 2026 and 2027, and integrated logistics support for the howitzers and 155&nbsp;mm ammunitions.<ref name="K9GF"/> This agreement did not involve loan like previous, and the deal includes technology transfers that allow Poland to manufacture 155&nbsp;mm ammunitions and K9 parts locally.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-12-27 |title=Tusk o kontraktach zbrojeniowych: przegląd z intencją kontynuacji |url=https://defence24.pl/polityka-obronna/tusk-o-kontraktach-zbrojeniowych-przeglad-z-intencja-kontynuacji |access-date=2023-12-31 |website=defence24.pl |language=pl}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-12-04 |title=K9 자주포 152문 폴란드 2차 수출 성공...한화 "3.4조 계약" |url=https://www.donga.com/news/Politics/article/all/20231204/122470501/1 |access-date=2023-12-05 |website=[[The Dong-A Ilbo]] |language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=2023-12-01 |title=Poland buys more K9 howitzers from South Korea in $2.6 billion deal |language=en |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/poland-buys-more-k9-howitzers-south-korea-26-billion-deal-2023-12-01/ |access-date=2023-12-05}}</ref> On the same day, a framework agreement for auxiliary vehicles for Krab and K9 howitzers was signed between the Polish MoD and PGZ, which means that Polish K9PL will be accompanied by domestic vehicles instead of the K10 or the K11.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-12-01 |title=Umowa na wozy towarzyszące dla polskich haubic |url=https://milmag.pl/umowa-na-wozy-towarzyszace-dla-polskich-haubic/ |access-date=2023-12-22 |website=MILMAG |language=pl-PL}}</ref>

The K9PL Batch II was initially described as "using solutions from the K9A2"; however, the final configuration from the December executive contract was the K9A1 with modifications.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-10-19 |title=Polskie haubice K9A1 zaprezentowane [FOTO] |url=https://defence24.pl/sily-zbrojne/polskie-haubice-k9a1-zaprezentowane-foto |access-date=2023-12-22 |website=defence24.pl |language=pl}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Walkowski |first=Antoni |date=2024-12-23 |title=Kraby i nie tylko. Rekordowe kontrakty Stalowej Woli |url=https://defence24.pl/sily-zbrojne/kraby-i-nie-tylko-rekordowe-kontrakty-stalowej-woli#goog_rewarded |access-date=2025-01-03 |website=defence24.pl |language=pl}}</ref> The Batch II has 13 additional subsystems compared to the first, such as the Obra-3 laser warning system, automatic fire suppression system in the crew compartment, air filtration system, air conditioning, smoke grenade launcher, and the APU in the chassis instead of in the turret.<ref name="K9GF"/><ref name=":0">{{Cite web |url=https://www.wojsko-polskie.pl/au/articles/aktualnosci/dodatkowe-haubice-samobiezne-dla-wojska-polskiego/ |title=Dodatkowe haubice samobieżne dla Wojska Polskiego|access-date=2023-12-22 |website=www.wojsko-polskie.pl |language=pl}}</ref>

On 16 March 2024, Korean banks authorized a maximum of $8.5 billion loan for Poland to purchase additional South Korean arms.<ref>{{Cite web |last=최 |first=은솔 |date=2024-03-17 |script-title=ko:폴란드 매체 국내 시중은행, 폴란드 무기수출에 10조원 대출 |url=https://www.ajunews.com/view/20240317153815788 |access-date=2024-08-27 |website=[[Aju Business Daily]] |language=ko}}</ref>

On 4 April 2024, Hanwha Aerospace opened a European office in Warsaw and announced the integration of the K9 and Krab howitzer systems with cooperation from HSW to improve the operational and maintenance efficiency of the Polish military. The two systems are simple to integrate since both use the same chassis. Hanwha Aerospace also plans to establish a MCS propellant production plant in Poland to support the entire 155&nbsp;mm artillery system.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-04-07 |script-title=ko:한화에어로스페이스, 폴란드와 K9 및 크라브 곡사포시스템 통합 협력 강화 |url=https://www.g-enews.com/ko-kr/news/article/news_all/20240407102246428e8b8a793f7_1/article.html |access-date=2024-08-28 |website=[[Global Economic (newspaper)|Global Economic]] |language=ko}}</ref> On 10 May 2024, two companies signed the letter of intent for the integration, which also includes adopting licensed PK9 chassis for the K9A2 and K9A3 and transferring technology for repairing the CN98 main gun.<ref>{{Cite web |title=HSW, Hanwha Aerospace to Integrate Polish Krab Chassis with Korean K9 Gun-Howitzers |url=https://www.defensemirror.com/news/36767/HSW__Hanwha_Aerospace_to_Integrate_Polish_Krab_Chassis_with_Korean_K9_Gun_Howitzers |access-date=2024-08-28 |website=www.defensemirror.com}}</ref>

On 23 December 2024, PGZ, HSW, and Rosomak SA were awarded PLN 8 billion for delivering more than 250 accompanying vehicles, including training and logistics package, for the K9 howitzers.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-12-23 |title=Polska Grupa Zbrojeniowa S.A. (lider), Huta Stalowa Wola S.A., Rosomak S.A., dostarczy #WojskoPolskie kilkaset wozów towarzyszących do haubic samobieżnych K9. |url=https://x.com/MON_GOV_PL/status/1871214773058121839 |website=x.com/ |publisher=Ministerstwo Obrony Narodowej}}</ref>

===Finland===
[[File:Dynamic Front 25 - Finnish Army K9 Moukari Self-Propelled Howitzer (8761382).jpg|thumb|right|[[Finnish Army]] K9FIN Moukari prepares to fire during exercise at [[Rovajärvi|Rovajärvi artillery range]]]]
On 1 June 2016 at KDEC (Korea Defense Equipment & Component) industry fair, two nations signed a MOU for defense cooperation including export of used K9.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hankookilbo.com/News/Read/201606020465675254 |title=K-9 자주포 40여문 핀란드 수출 임박 |publisher=[[Hankook Ilbo]] |date=2016-06-02}}</ref> In July 2016, the Finnish Ministry of Defence announced that an undisclosed number of used K9s have been selected to be acquired from the Republic of Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defmin.fi/ajankohtaista/tiedotteet/maavoimien_tykistokaluston_uusiminen_etenee.7898.news|title=Maavoimien tykistökaluston uusiminen etenee|access-date=2016-07-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160705051603/http://www.defmin.fi/ajankohtaista/tiedotteet/maavoimien_tykistokaluston_uusiminen_etenee.7898.news|archive-date=2016-07-05|url-status=live}}</ref> The acquisition is claimed to be biggest of the decade for the Land Forces, whose both mobile and towed artillery face mass outdating in the 2020s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reservilainen.fi/uutiset/maavoimien_etsikkoaikaa_eletaan_parhaillaan|title=Maavoimien etsikkoaikaa eletään parhaillaan|date=26 February 2016|access-date=1 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160608153559/http://www.reservilainen.fi/uutiset/maavoimien_etsikkoaikaa_eletaan_parhaillaan|archive-date=8 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2016, K9 was field tested in Finland, and Seppo Toivonen, the commander of the Finnish Army, visited South Korea to inspect operating units during 2016 DX Korea.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.khan.co.kr/politics/defense-diplomacy/article/201609182238005 |script-title=ko:핀란드 육군사령관, K-9 자주포 부대 다녀가 |publisher=[[Kyunghyang Shinmun]] |date=2016-09-18}}</ref> On 25 November 2016, two countries signed MOU to supply 48 used K9 for $200 million and match equal amount of free technology transfer related to vehicle maintenance.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.intn.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=731956 |title=K-9 자주포, 핀란드 수출 양해각서 체결 |publisher=Daily NTN |date=2016-11-23}}</ref>

On 17 February 2017, the Ministry of Defense announced that Finland will acquire 48 used K9s over a period of seven years starting in 2018, with conscript training on the equipment commencing in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yle.fi/uutiset/3-9466486|title=Suomi ostaa 48 käytettyä panssarihaupitsia Etelä-Koreasta|website=Yle Uutiset|date=17 February 2017|access-date=2017-02-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217152142/http://yle.fi/uutiset/3-9466486|archive-date=2017-02-17|url-status=live}}</ref> On 2 March 2017, final contract of value of €145 million ($160 million) was signed by two governments in Seoul, South Korea.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.korea.kr/news/pressReleaseView.do?newsId=156186646 |title=K-9 자주포 핀란드 수출계약 체결, 48문 1.45억 유로 규모 |publisher=Republic of Korea |date=2017-03-02}}</ref>

On 21 October 2021, Finnish Ministry of Defense authorized exercising option to purchase 10 new vehicles including spare parts and supplies—5 in 2021 and another 5 in 2022—for €30 million, increasing the fleet size to 58 vehicles.<ref>{{cite web|title=Finnish Army to use option for 5 additional K9 155 mm self-propelled howitzers {{!}} Defense News October 2021 Global Security army industry {{!}} Defense Security global news industry army year 2021 {{!}} Archive News year|url=https://www.armyrecognition.com/defense_news_october_2021_global_security_army_industry/finnish_army_to_use_option_for_5_additional_k9_155_mm_self-propelled_howitzers.html|access-date=2021-10-28|website=www.armyrecognition.com|date=22 October 2021 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Finland exercises option for five more K9 SPHs|url=https://www.janes.com/defence-news/news-detail/finland-exercises-option-for-five-more-k9-sphs|access-date=2021-10-28|website=Janes.com|date=25 October 2021 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lisää K9-panssarihaupitseja Maavoimille – Ruotuväki|url=https://ruotuvaki.fi/-/lisaa-k9-panssarihaupitseja-maavoimille|access-date=2021-10-29|website=ruotuvaki.fi|date=26 October 2021|language=fi-FI}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=박 |first=원석 |date=2024-09-09 |script-title=ko:서울대 '2024 한-핀란드 이노베이션 포럼: 떠오르는 민/군 겸용 기술' 개최 |url=https://www.veritas-a.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=519420 |access-date=2024-09-19 |website=[[Veritas Alpha]] |language=ko}}</ref>

On 18 November 2022 Finnish Minister of Defence [[Antti Kaikkonen]] authorized purchase of another 38 used vehicles for €134 million.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.hs.fi/kotimaa/art-2000009211493.html/ |newspaper=hs.fi|access-date=2022-11-18|date=2022-11-18|title=Suomi jatkaa aseostoja Venäjän hyökkäyssodan varjossa: Nyt ostoslistalla on liki 40 "Moukaria"}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-03-07 |script-title=ko:[더구루] 핀란드, K9 중고 자주포 개량 추진…밀로그 낙점 |url=https://www.theguru.co.kr/news/article.html?no=67648 |access-date=2024-09-19 |website=www.theguru.co.kr |language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web  |date=2025-05-11 |script-title=ko:다올證 "핀란드, K9 자주포 추가 구매… 주변국 구매 욕구 자극 기대" |url=https://biz.chosun.com/stock/stock_general/2025/05/12/JNJJAGHOZZCBPEIU4JJSEEEEBQ/ |access-date=2025-05-29 |website=[[ChosunBiz]] |language=ko}}</ref>

The official Finnish designation of the howitzer is '''155 PSH K9 FIN''', colloquially called Moukari (meaning Sledgehammer). Vehicles receive domestic modification via Millog.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://puolustusvoimat.fi/en/equipment#/asset/view/id/234 | title=Materiel and Equipment of the Finnish Defence Forces }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-09-23 |title=K9 howitzer delivery to Finland continues |url=https://en.defenceturk.net/k9-howitzer-delivery-to-finland-continues/ |access-date=2023-12-20 |website=English Defence News |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-04-11 |title=Millog – a pioneer in national security of supply |url=https://defence-industry.eu/millog-a-pioneer-in-national-security-of-supply/ |access-date=2023-12-20 |language=en}}</ref>

On 4 March 2024, Millog signed a contract with the Finnish Defense Force to upgrade 48 vehicles purchased in 2021 and 2022 at €8.1 million. The work is expected to be completed by 2030.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-03-04 |title=Millog sai lisätilauksen Puolustusvoimilta K9-panssarihaupitsien käyttökuntoon saattamisesta |url=https://millog.fi/millog-sai-lisatilauksen-puolustusvoimilta-k9-panssarihaupitsien-kayttokuntoon-saattamisesta/ |access-date=2024-03-07 |website=Millog |language=fi}}</ref>

