===Norway===
[[File:U S , Allied forces present military equipment display for media in Norway during exercise (8915732).jpg|thumb|[[Norwegian Army]] K9 VIDAR on display at the [[Setermoen]] Training Area in Norway on March 14, 2025.]]
In May 2015, Samsung Techwin joined the Norwegian artillery upgrade program, competing against the [[Krauss-Maffei Wegmann|KMW]] Panzerhaubitze 2000, the [[Nexter Systems|Nexter]] [[CAESAR self-propelled howitzer|CAESAR 6x6]], and the [[RUAG]] [[M109 howitzer#M109 KAWEST|M109 KAWEST]] to replace Norway's M109Gs with 24 new systems.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.idaegu.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=164750 |script-title=ko:장윤석 의원, 노르웨이와 방산·문화 협력 논의 |publisher=Daegu Newspaper |date=2015-05-20}}</ref> A single K9 was sent to Norway to join the competition. Operated by a sales team, the vehicle went through tests between November 2015 and January 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.segye.com/newsView/20160207001259?OutUrl=naver |script-title=ko:노르웨이 설원에 간 자주포 K9 |publisher=Segye |date=2016-02-07 |newspaper=[[Segye Ilbo]] |last1=Com |first1=Segye }}</ref> During the January winter test, the K9 was the only vehicle that managed to drive through meter-thick snow field and fire its weapon without any issue. Competing vehicles experienced engine troubles or broken parts.<ref name="salesperson interview" /><ref name="CEO Interview"/>

The K9's engine was able to maintain heat overnight by simply covering the area with tarpaulin, a simple trick learned from operating experience, allowing the engine to ignite without failure the next day at an extremely cold temperature. The hydropneumatic suspension became a huge advantage for mobility, as its mechanism melted snow on mobility parts much quicker. The test result also impacted Finland and Estonia, who were invited to observe performances for their artillery replacement, to acquire the K9.<ref name="salesperson interview" /><ref name="CEO Interview">{{cite news |url=https://segye.com/view/20180220004415 |script-title=ko:손재일 한화지상방산 대표 "K-9, 해외마케팅 강화 |publisher=Segye |date=2018-02-20 |newspaper=[[Segye Ilbo]] |last1=Com |first1=Segye }}</ref>

In August 2016, the Norwegian Defence Materiel Agency published their intention to continue negotiations with Hanwha Techwin and RUAG, while Krauss-Maffei Wegmann and Nexter Systems had been put "on hold". Unnamed sources in the Norwegian Army had previously stated that the K9 was a leading candidate in the competition.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tu.no/artikler/haeren-ligger-an-til-a-fa-koreanske-kanoner/350619 |author=Per Erlien Dalløkken |title=Hæren ligger an til å få koreanske kanoner |trans-title=The army is likely to get Korean cannons |language=no |publisher=tu.no |date=24 August 2016 |access-date=24 August 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160825165759/http://www.tu.no/artikler/haeren-ligger-an-til-a-fa-koreanske-kanoner/350619 |archive-date=25 August 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>

In December 2017, a contract of $230 million was signed between Hanwha Land Systems and the Norwegian Ministry of Defense, for supplying 24 K9 Thunder and 6 K10 ARV by 2020. The K9 outperformed competitors in various weather and terrain conditions according to Norwegian military officials during trials.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.yna.co.kr/view/AKR20171221023351014?input=1195m |script-title=ko:한화, K-9 자주포 24문 노르웨이에 수출 계약...2천452억원 규모(종합) |publisher=[[Yonhap News Agency]] |date=2017-12-21 |newspaper=[[Yonhap News Agency]] |author1=김귀근 }}</ref>

The Norwegian variant was named '''K9 VIDAR''' (versatile indirect artillery system), and is based on the K9A1 configuration. It differs from the K9A1 by changing the BTCS to a Norwegian ODIN fire support system and radio communication systems for [[NATO]] operation. It mounts the gunner's sight for direct firing, and installed spall liner for additional protection.<ref name="Defense Today K9" /><ref name="Defense Times">{{cite web |date=2019-10-05 |title=K9A1 자주포의 시작 |language=ko |url=http://defensetimes.kr/article/view.php?&ss[fc]=4&bbs_id=DefenceTimes_news&doc_num=1754 |publisher=Defense Times}}</ref><ref name="Manufacturer Interview">{{cite AV media |date=2020-11-08 |script-title=ko:[군금해?!] K9A3 완전무인화? 우리가 몰랐던 K9자주포의 모든 것! |language=ko |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kRM7R2FOhBY |publisher=국방TV}}</ref> Norwegian company [[Kongsberg Gruppen|Kongsberg]] participated in upgrading the K9 for Norway, Finland, and Estonia. The company will partner with Hanwha Defense again for Australia's AS9 program.<ref>{{cite web|date=2020-11-13|script-title=ko:한화디펜스, 호주 자주포 사업 수주 '히든카드' 꺼내...콩스버그 협력|url=http://www.theguru.co.kr/news/article.html?no=16146|access-date=2021-09-01|website=www.theguru.co.kr|language=ko}}</ref>

In November 2022, Norway used an option signed in 2017, to purchase 4 K9s and 8 K10s, increasing its total vehicles to 28 K9s and 14 K10s (2:1 ratio).<ref>{{Cite web |last=이 |first=보람 |date=2022-11-08 |script-title=ko:한화에어로스페이스, 노르웨이에 K9 자주포 추가 수출 |url=https://www.joongang.co.kr/article/25115902 |access-date=2022-12-02 |website=[[JoongAng Ilbo]] |language=ko}}</ref> The delivery is expected to be completed in 2 years.<ref>{{Cite web |last=박 |first=희준 |date=2022-11-09 |script-title=ko:노르웨이, K9 4문·K10 8대 추가 수입...K9 수입량 총 28문 |url=http://news.tf.co.kr/read/world/1977870.htm |access-date=2022-12-02 |website=더팩트 |language=ko}}</ref>

In April 2025, it was announced that Norway plans to almost double its K9s by ordering an additional 24 K9s for about $534 million USD.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Ruitenberg |first=Rudy |date=2025-04-04 |title=Norway to nearly double its K9 howitzer fleet for around $534 million |url=https://www.defensenews.com/global/europe/2025/04/04/norway-to-nearly-double-its-k9-howitzer-fleet-for-around-534-million/ |access-date=2025-04-04 |website=Defense News |language=en}}</ref> The contract for the third batch was signed on 19 September 2025.<ref name="Norway 3rd">{{Cite web |date=2025-09-19 |title=한화에어로스페이스, 노르웨이와 'K9 자주포' 24문 추가 계약… 총 52문 공급 |url=https://www.donga.com/news/Economy/article/all/20250919/132425285/1 |access-date=2025-09-20 |website=동아일보 |language=ko}}</ref>

===Estonia===
[[File:K9 Kõu.jpg|thumb|right|K9EST Kõu during maneuver training.]]

To reduce the cost per unit for both nations, Finland invited Estonia to jointly procure the K9. Under this arrangement, Finland provided test data on the K9 to Estonia, with approval from South Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baltic-course.com/eng/baltic_states/?doc=127392|title=Estonia to team up with Finland to procure K9 Thunder howitzers|author=The Baltic Course (Балтийский курс)|access-date=2017-02-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203191818/http://www.baltic-course.com/eng/baltic_states/?doc=127392|archive-date=2017-02-03|url-status=live}}</ref> In February 2017, Estonian military officials visited South Korea for price negotiations.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ajunews.com/view/20170206183444057 |title=K-9자주포 유럽 2개국에 동시수출 |language=ko |publisher=[[Aju Business Daily]] |date=2017-02-06}}</ref>

In June 2018, [[Rauno Sirk]], the director of the Estonian military procurement agency, announced that Estonia would buy K9 Thunder howitzers. Hanwha Land Systems was to supply 12 used K9s for €46 million, which would cover maintenance, parts and training, as in the contract with Finland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://estonianworld.com/security/estonia-to-buy-artillery-from-south-korea-for-e46-million/|title=Estonia to buy artillery from South Korea for €46 million|last=Hankewitz|first=Sten|date=26 June 2018|work=Estonian World|access-date=27 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180628055638/http://estonianworld.com/security/estonia-to-buy-artillery-from-south-korea-for-e46-million/|archive-date=28 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://newsis.com/view/?id=NISX20180626_0000347123&cID=10101&pID=10100 |script-title=ko:에스토니아, K9 자주포 12대 600억원에 도입 합의 |language=ko |publisher=[[Newsis]] |date=2018-06-27}}</ref> In October 2019, the Estonian Ministry of Defense announced that it would exercise the option to purchase 6 additional K9s under the terms of this contract, at an estimated cost of €20 million.<ref>{{cite web |date=2019-10-25 |script-title=ko:한화디펜스, 에스토니아에 K9 자주포 6대 추가 수출 |url=https://www.g-enews.com/view.php?ud=201910250802595817c5557f8da8_1 |access-date=2021-08-31 |website=[[Global Economic (newspaper)|Global Economic]] |trans-website=Global Economics |language=ko}}</ref>

In August 2021, the Estonian Centre for Defense Investment (RKIK) signed a €4.6 million contract with Hanwha Defense and Go Craft to modernize 24 '''K9EST Kõu''', hinting at purchasing 6 more for its inventory. The upgrade involves communication systems, a FCS, painting, fire suppression system, and electronics.<ref>{{cite web |date=2021-08-04 |script-title=ko:에스토니아군, 한화디펜스와 함께 K9 자주포 개조 착수...6문 추가 구매설 |url=https://www.g-enews.com/view.php?ud=2021080410262139c5557f8da8_1 |access-date=2021-09-01 |website=[[Global Economic (newspaper)|Global Economic]] |trans-website=Global Economics |language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=2021-08-05|script-title=ko:한화디펜스, 에스토니아 'K9 자주포' 현대화 사업 수주|url=http://www.theguru.co.kr/news/article.html?no=23955|access-date=2021-09-01|website=www.theguru.co.kr|language=ko}}</ref>

In September 2022, it was reported that Estonia had purchased 24 vehicles in total.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-09-22 |script-title=ko:합참의장, 에스토니아 총사령관 접견...군사·방산협력 논의 |url=https://www.ytn.co.kr/_ln/0101_202209221716198367 |access-date=2022-09-28 |website=[[YTN]] |language=ko}}</ref><ref name="K9 Estonia service">{{Cite web |script-title=ko:한·에스토니아, 군사 교류 확대 '긴밀한 협력' |url=https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220923/1/BBSMSTR_000000010022/view.do |access-date=2022-09-28 |website=[[Global Economic (newspaper)|Global Economic]] |trans-website=The Korea Defense Daily |language=ko |archive-date=13 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221213061917/https://kookbang.dema.mil.kr/newsWeb/20220923/1/BBSMSTR_000000010022/view.do |url-status=dead }}</ref> In October, the Estonian defense minister stated that Estonia would procure 12 additional K9s, bringing the total number up to 36 units.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://breakingdefense.com/2022/11/estonias-defense-minister-on-ukranian-lessons-future-investments-and-russias-cyber-threat/ |title=Estonia's defense minister on Ukrainian lessons, future investments and Russia's cyber threat |last=Mehta |first=Aaron |date=7 November 2022 |website=Breaking Defense |access-date=12 July 2024}}</ref> In November 2022, Go Craft opened Estonia's first private military workshop, and will start upgrading K9s.<ref>{{Cite web |author=<!--not stated--> |editor-last=Turovski |editor-first=Marcus |date=2022-11-30 |title=Go Craft opens first private military equipment service and repair workshop |url=https://news.err.ee/1608805537/go-craft-opens-first-private-military-equipment-service-and-repair-workshop |access-date=2022-12-09 |website=[[Eesti Rahvusringhääling]] |language=en}}</ref> In January 2023, Estonia ordered 12 vehicles for €36 million, which will be delivered before 2026.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-01-17 |script-title=ko:[단독] 한화에어로, 에스토니아와 'K9 자주포' 12문 추가 계약 ... 3600만 유로 |url=https://biz.newdaily.co.kr/site/data/html/2023/01/17/2023011700037.html |access-date=2023-05-15 |website=[[Global Economic (newspaper)|Global Economic]] |trans-website=[[Newdaily]] |language=ko}}</ref> The first Estonian edition by Go Craft was rolled out in February 2023.<ref>{{Cite web |author=<!--not stated--> |editor1-last=Whyte |editor1-first=Andrew |editor2-last=Nael |editor2-first=Merili |date=2023-02-23 |title=EDF takes delivery of first K9 to be fitted out for Estonian conditions |url=https://news.err.ee/1608894809/edf-takes-delivery-of-first-k9-to-be-fitted-out-for-estonian-conditions |access-date=2023-05-15 |website=[[Eesti Rahvusringhääling]] |language=en}}</ref>

