In June 2005 in Australia, the defense ministers of the two nations held a meeting and discussed trading opportunities involving K9 Thunder and Australian 5-inch naval gun ammunition.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.naver.com/main/read.naver?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=102&oid=022&aid=0000100009 |script-title=ko:국산 K-9자주포 호주수출 추진 |publisher=Segye |date=2005-06-01}}</ref> In August 2009, it was reported that the consortium of [[Samsung Techwin]] and [[Raytheon Australia]] had the upper hand for Australia's Land 17 artillery replacement program by becoming a sole bidder, as [[Krauss-Maffei Wegmann|KMW]], the manufacturer of the competing [[Panzerhaubitze 2000]], had not provided the detailed offering proposal that Australia requested.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seoul.co.kr/news/newsView.php?id=20090804004011 |title=K-9 자주포 호주 수출 유력 |publisher=[[Seoul Shinmun]] |date=2009-08-04}}</ref>

The K9 was sent to Australia, and was evaluated by the Australian military starting in April 2010. The test included firing [[M982 Excalibur]], a requirement which the K9 satisfied. The Australian variant '''AS9''' was expected to feature a NATO standard [[fire-control system]], the BMS-F (Battlefield Management System – Fires), the RWS (Remote Weapon System), and anti-tank mine protection. The hydropneumatic suspension was enhanced to support its increased weight.<ref name="Defense Today K9" />

In June 2010, the K9 became the preferred bidder for the LAND 17 program. The project budget was redirected for restoration due to the [[2010–2011 Queensland floods|floods in Queensland]] in 2011, which led to the cancelation of the project in May 2012.<ref name="salesperson interview" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newdaily.co.kr/site/data/html/2012/04/26/2012042600032.html |title=K-9 자주포, 호주 땅도 밟을까 |publisher=[[Newdaily]] |date=2012-04-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lane |first=Sabra |date=3 May 2012 |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-05-03/defence-white-paper-now-due-in-2013/3987042 |title=Defence projects scrapped to save billions |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] |access-date=3 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503202448/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-05-03/defence-white-paper-now-due-in-2013/3987042 |archive-date=3 May 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2019, in the lead-up to the 2019 Federal Election, the Prime Minister of Australia, Scott Morrison, announced that 30 K9 howitzers and associated support equipment, including ten K10 ammunition resupply vehicles, would be acquired for the ADF. No time frame was given for the purchase.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Bergmann |first=Kym |date=June 2019 |title=Australian Army to receive massive boost in firepower with 155mm SPH purchase |url=https://search.informit.org/doi/abs/10.3316/agispt.20190702013378 |url-access=subscription |journal=Asia-Pacific Defence Reporter |volume=45 |issue=5 |pages=12–16 |issn=1446-6880}}</ref>

In September 2020, the Minister for Defense, Linda Reynolds, announced a request for tender to locally build 30 K9s under the Land 8116 Phase 1 Protected Mobility Fires requirement. The sole-source request for tender will be released to the preferred supplier, Hanwha Defense Australia, to build and maintain 30 K9s and 15 K10s, as well as their supporting systems. These will be built at Hanwha Defense Australia's Geelong facility. Australian variant '''AS9 Huntsman''' is based on Norwegian K9 VIDAR. It will retain the options offered in 2010 with up-to-date modifications.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.defenceconnect.com.au/land-amphibious/6760-government-announces-request-for-tender-for-army-protected-mobile-fires? |title=Government announces request for tender for Army Protected Mobile Fires |last=Kuper |first=Stephen |date=2 September 2020 |website=Defence Connect |access-date=12 July 2024}}</ref>

In December 2021, the Capability Acquisition and Sustainment Group (CASG) of Australia and Hanwha Defense Australia signed a formal contract of producing 30 AS9s and 15 '''AS10 AARV'''s under license at Hanwha Defense Australia facility in [[Geelong]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]; the facility, which is included in the contract, will begin its construction in Q2 2022. The CASG and the DAPA also signed an MOU for defense cooperation between the two countries. The estimated value of the deal is $788 million, and manufacturing is expected to start in Q4 2024.<ref>{{cite web|date=2021-12-13|script-title=ko:파이브 아이즈도 'K9 자주포' 쏜다...한화, 호주에 1조 규모 수출 – 머니투데이|url=https://news.mt.co.kr/mtview.php?no=2021121311453525987|access-date=2021-12-13|website=[[Money Today]]|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=S. Korea to export 30 units of K-9 howitzer to Australia under W930b deal|url=https://www.koreaherald.com/article/2739837|access-date=2021-12-13|website=[[The Korea Herald]] |date=13 December 2021 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Kadib |first=Charbel |date=2021-12-13 |title=Huntsman deal to strengthen regional security posture: PM |url=https://www.defenceconnect.com.au/key-enablers/9245-huntsman-deal-to-strengthen-regional-security-posture-pm |website=Defence Connect |publisher=Momentum Media |access-date=2021-12-13}}</ref>

In February 2022, Hanwha Defense Australia made a selection of site of 150,000 m<sup>2</sup>, which includes 32,000 m<sup>2</sup> manufacturing facility, 1.5&nbsp;km long track, and various test and R&D sites, for its first overseas factory named H-ACE (Hanwha Armoured Vehicle Centre of Excellence) at Geelong, which will create 300 jobs for local specialists. Construction began on 8 April, and is expected to take 2 years to complete.<ref name="Australia Factory 1" /><ref name="Australia Factory 2" /><ref>{{Cite web  |date=2022-04-08 |script-title=ko:호주 현지에 한국산 자주포·장갑차 생산 공장 생긴다 |url=https://www.newsis.com/view/?id=NISX20220408_0001826206 |access-date=2022-06-05 |website=[[Newsis]] |language=ko}}</ref>

In March 2022, Hanwha Defense signed a $67 million deal with Norwegian firm [[Kongsberg Gruppen]] for the installation of C4 for Australian vehicles. Kongsberg is expected to supply Integrated Combat Solution (ICS) as well as ODIN fire support systems via Kongsberg Australia.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-03-11 |script-title=ko:한화디펜스, '1조' 호주 자주포 수출 프로젝트 잰걸음 |url=http://www.theguru.co.kr/news/article.html?no=32404 |access-date=2022-06-05 |website=www.theguru.co.kr |language=ko}}</ref> On 19 July, Hanwha Systems signed a contract with Hanwha Defense Australia to supply HUMS (Health and Usage Monitoring System) and Situational Awareness System (SAS) for AS9s and AS10s at a cost of 20.8 billion KRW.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-07-20 |script-title=ko:한화시스템-한화디펜스-원웹, 호주軍 위성인터넷 사업 협력 MOU 체결 |url=https://www.lawissue.co.kr/view.php?ud=202207201903331922204ead0791_12 |access-date=2022-07-23 |website=로이슈}}</ref>

In October 2022, Hanwha signed a $5 million deal with Safran to supply 32 MINEO DFSS for direct firing capability.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-10-05 |script-title=ko:한화 '호주 자주포 사업'에 프랑스 사프란 가세 |url=http://www.theguru.co.kr/news/article.html?no=43116 |access-date=2023-05-15 |website=www.theguru.co.kr |language=ko}}</ref> In January 2023, Hanwha signed a $3.5 million contract with a German company AirSense Analytics to supply CBRN system for the vehicles.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-01-30 |script-title=ko:한화에어로, K9 호주형 모델에 독일산 화학·유해물질 센서 탑재 |url=http://www.theguru.co.kr/news/article.html?no=48948 |access-date=2023-05-15 |website=www.theguru.co.kr |language=ko}}</ref>

In April 2023, Australia withdrew from Land 8116 Phase 2, a repeating order equal to Phase 1 in volume, as the new government decided to focus on [[M142 HIMARS]], air, and naval assets.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-04-24 |script-title=ko:한화에어로 '호주몽' 비상등...장갑차 축소·자주포 추가 도입 중단 |url=http://www.theguru.co.kr/news/article.html?no=52839 |access-date=2023-05-15 |website=www.theguru.co.kr |language=ko}}</ref>

In May 2023, Israeli firm [[Plasan]] completed the protection test for the program.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-06-01 |script-title=ko:한화, 호주 '헌츠맨 프로젝트' AS9·AS10 폭발 테스트 성공적 완료 |url=http://www.theguru.co.kr/news/article.html?no=54621 |access-date=2023-08-26 |website=www.theguru.co.kr |language=ko}}</ref>

Production of AS9 and AS10 began in June 2023.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-06-28 |script-title=ko:[모닝픽] 한화디펜스, 호주서 K9자주포·K10 탄약보급장갑차 생산 시작 |url=https://www.g-enews.com/article/Global-Biz/2023/06/2023062807492176356ed0c62d49_1 |access-date=2023-08-26 |website=[[Global Economic (newspaper)|Global Economic]] |language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-06-28 |script-title=ko:한화에어로스페이스, 호주軍 공급용 K9자주포 양산 개시 |url=http://www.theguru.co.kr/news/article.html?no=55894 |access-date=2023-08-26 |website=www.theguru.co.kr |language=ko}}</ref> In July, Australian army conducted tests on ammunition compatibility at the Agency for Defense Development test center in South Korea.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-07-04 |script-title=ko:호주 육군, 한화 'AS9 자주포' 포탄 발사 테스트 진행 |url=http://www.theguru.co.kr/news/article.html?no=56228 |access-date=2023-08-26 |website=www.theguru.co.kr |language=ko}}</ref> In August, another Israeli company Epsilor was selected to supply NATO standard 6T Li-ion batteries for the howitzer.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-08-22 |script-title=ko:호주, K9 자주포에 이스라엘산 전력 시스템 장착 |url=http://www.hansbiz.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=661187 |access-date=2023-08-26 |website=한스경제 |language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=6T Li-Ion NATO Batteries |url=https://www.epsilor.com/product/6t-li-ion-nato-batteries/ |access-date=2023-08-26 |website=Epsilor |language=en-US}}</ref>

On 28 March 2024, Hanwha Aerospace announced the beginning of assembly of two AS9s and one AS10 in Changwon. The remaining 28 AS9s and 14 AS10s will be built at H-ACE in Australia.<ref>{{Cite web |script-title=ko:한화에어로스페이스 '호주 육군용 AS9 자주포' 창원 공장서 첫 생산 돌입 |url=https://www.munhwa.com/news/view.html?no=2024033101039930114003 |access-date=2024-08-28 |website=[[Munhwa Ilbo]] | date=31 March 2024 |language=ko}}</ref>

On 23 August 2024, Hanwha Aerospace invited Korean and Australian government officials for an opening ceremony of H-ACE. The factory will start mass production of AS9 and AS10 in that year and deliver all vehicles to the Australian Army by 2027.<ref>{{Cite web |last=강 |first=지용 |date=2024-08-23 |script-title=ko:한화에어로스페이스, 호주 방산 생산기지 완공…국내 첫 해외 생산 |url=https://www.financialpost.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=211662 |access-date=2024-08-30 |website=파이낸셜포스트 |language=ko}}</ref>

In December 2024, Hanwha Aerospace delivered two AS9 and one AS10 to Hanwha Defence Australia, and the Australian military received them in January 2025.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Vandenbosch |title=Australia Officially Receives Its First AS9 Huntsman Vehicles from South Korea |url=https://armyrecognition.com/news/army-news/2025/australia-officially-receives-its-first-as9-huntsman-vehicles-from-south-korea |access-date=2025-02-08 |website=armyrecognition.com |language=en-gb}}</ref>

===Egypt===

In 2010, the K9 was evaluated by the Egyptian military to replace its aging artillery fleet. The deal was delayed when the Egyptian government requested a reduction on technology transfer fees, which would have required the South Korean government's approval. The negotiations ended as regional instability due to the [[Arab Spring]] caused the Egyptian government to postpone the project indefinitely.<ref name="salesperson interview" />

In April 2017, it was reported that Hanwha Techwin was again in negotiations with Egypt to export the K9 Thunder.<ref name="businesspost.co.kr">{{cite news |url= http://www.businesspost.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=46398 |title= Hanwha Techwin to improve earnings due to K9 Thunder exports |date= 5 April 2017 |website=비즈니스포스트 |trans-website=Business Post |language= ko |access-date= 24 August 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170825020136/http://www.businesspost.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=46398 |archive-date= 25 August 2017 |url-status= live }}</ref> A K9 howitzer was sent to Egypt in July and was test-fired at a range located west of Cairo in August, along with competitors such as the French [[CAESAR self-propelled howitzer|CAESAR]], Russian [[2S35 Koalitsiya-SV]], and Chinese [[PLZ-45]].<ref name="defenceweb.co.za">{{cite news |url= http://www.defenceweb.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=48661 |title= Egypt evaluating new artillery |date= 24 July 2017 |language= en |access-date= 24 August 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170825020846/http://www.defenceweb.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=48661 |archive-date= 25 August 2017 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mbn.co.kr/news/world/3294251 |title=K-9 자주포 이집트서 시험발사...성능평가 후 수출 기대 |publisher=[[Maeil Broadcasting Network]] |date=2017-07-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Helou|first=Agnes|date=2022-02-01|title=Why did Egypt choose to buy South Korea's K9 howitzer?|url=https://www.defensenews.com/land/2022/02/01/why-did-egypt-choose-to-buy-south-koreas-k9-howitzer/|access-date=2022-02-20|website=Defense News|language=en}}</ref> During the test, the K9 hit a target ship approaching to the shore, successfully performing an [[anti-access/area denial]] simulation against enemy ships for the [[Egyptian Navy]].<ref>{{cite web|date=2022-02-03|script-title=ko:곡사 화기로 망망대해 표적 저격...K9에 반한 이집트, K10·K11도 담았다|url=https://news.mt.co.kr/mtview.php?no=2022020309170864535|access-date=2022-02-20|website=[[Money Today]]|language=ko}}</ref><ref name="K9 Egypt & K9A2" />

In October 2021, the two nations discussed the sale of the K9 Thunder. The estimated value of the deal was $2 billion, including training of technicians.<ref>{{cite web|last=남 |first=수현|date=2021-10-12|script-title=ko:박병석, 이집트 대통령 만나 세일즈 외교|url=https://www.joongang.co.kr/article/25014005|access-date=2021-10-12|website=[[JoongAng Ilbo]]|language=ko}}</ref> In the same month, the Egyptian minister of military production visited Hanwha Defense and Hyundai WIA facility to see the manufacturing process of the K9 Thunder and K2 Black Panther respectively.<ref>{{cite web|date=2021-10-25|script-title=ko:[단독] 이집트 방산물자부장관, 한화디펜스·현대위아 공장 방문|url=http://www.theguru.co.kr/news/article.html?no=26706|access-date=2021-12-12|website=www.theguru.co.kr|language=ko}}</ref> The two parties, including Egyptian president [[Abdel Fattah el-Sisi]], met again at the EDEX 2021 exposition to discuss the export of the howitzer.<ref>{{cite web|date=2021-11-30|script-title=ko:한화디펜스 K9 자주포, 이집트 수출길 오르나...한·이집트 군당국 논의|url=http://www.theguru.co.kr/news/article.html?no=28357|access-date=2021-12-12|website=www.theguru.co.kr|language=ko}}</ref> Egypt was reportedly looking to produce the howitzer under license.<ref>{{cite web|date=2021-12-11|script-title=ko:[여의옥] 한화, 'K9 자주포' 이집트 수출 물밑협상|url=http://www.theguru.co.kr/news/article.html?no=28872|access-date=2021-12-12|website=www.theguru.co.kr|language=ko}}</ref>

In February 2022, South Korea's [[Defense Acquisition Program Administration]] (DAPA) announced that [[Hanwha Defense]] had signed a $1.6 billion K9 Thunder export contract at Egypt's Artillery House, attended by Egypt's Ministry of National Defense and key officials from both countries. Egypt also signed a loan contract with South Korea. According to DAPA, the deal provided for the production of 200 '''K9A1EGY''' and 100 '''K10EGY''' in Egypt, including technology transfer.<ref name="K9 Egypt export">{{cite news|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20220201001900325|title=S. Korea to export K9 howitzers to Egypt in 2 tln won deal|newspaper=[[Yonhap News Agency]]|date=1 February 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220201160416/https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20220201001900325|archive-date=1 February 2022|access-date=1 February 2022|last1=Kang |first1=Yoon-Seung }}</ref><ref name="Yonhap1">{{cite web|url=https://news.naver.com/main/read.naver?mode=LPOD&mid=sec&oid=001&aid=0012952423&isYeonhapFlash=Y&rc=N|title=K-9 자주포, 2조원대 이집트 수출 극적 성사...아프리카 첫 진출|publisher=[[Yonhap News Agency]]|date=1 February 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220201101652/https://news.naver.com/main/read.naver?mode=LPOD&mid=sec&oid=001&aid=0012952423&isYeonhapFlash=Y&rc=N|archive-date=1 February 2022|access-date=1 February 2022|author=Jung Bitna}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Hanwha Defense inks deal to export the K9 Self-Propelled Howitzer to Egypt| date=3 February 2022 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rVtdknJE0m0|language=en|access-date=2022-02-20}}</ref> An unknown number of the earliest vehicles in the series were to be produced in South Korea and delivered to the [[Egyptian Army]] and the Egyptian Navy.<ref>{{cite web|date=2022-02-03|script-title=ko:한화디펜스, 이집트와 K9 자주포 2조원 규모 수출 계약...'역대 최대 규모'|url=http://www.ftoday.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=231376|access-date=2022-02-20|website=파이낸셜투데이|trans-website=Financial Today|language=ko}}</ref><ref name="Egypt Engine"/><ref>{{Cite web |last=임 |first=재현 |title="K9 이집트 자주포 수출 계약, 금융조건 합의했다"...수출입은행, 일각 비판에 정면 반박 |url=https://www.ddaily.co.kr//page/view/2022021613320571583 |access-date=2023-12-31 |website=디지털데일리 |trans-website=Digital Daily |language=ko}}</ref> On 25 February, two more contracts involving parts purchase and assembly were signed at the Military Factory 200, a state-owned Egyptian arms manufacturer.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-02-26 |script-title=ko:한화디펜스, 이집트와 K-9자주포 공동생산 후속계약 체결 |url=https://www.g-enews.com/article/Industry/2022/02/2022022615531936614fb262fcb_1 |access-date=2022-06-05 |website=[[Global Economic (newspaper)|Global Economic]] |trans-website=Global Economics |language=ko}}</ref>

The production of the first K9A1EGY was expected in Q4 2022, with armor steel provided by Bisalloy Steels. The first batch was to be delivered to Egypt until 2024, while the rest will be produced in Egypt with a localization rate of 50%. Egypt is expecting to increase localization to 67% in five years.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-06-12 |script-title=ko:한화, 이집트 K9사업 파트너로 호주 철강기업 낙점 |url=http://www.theguru.co.kr/news/article.html?no=36630 |access-date=2022-07-18 |website=www.theguru.co.kr |language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=tf.co.kr |date=2022-06-19 |script-title=ko:이집트 내년부터 K9A1EGY 자주 포 생산...아랍·아프리카 수출협의 |url=http://news.tf.co.kr/read/world/1946099.htm |access-date=2022-06-19 |website=더팩트 |trans-website=The Fact |language=ko}}</ref> On 22 October 2022, Hanwha Defense signed a contract with Arab International Optronics to transfer automatic fire control system (AFCS) and other substantial technologies.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-10-24 |script-title=ko:한화디펜스, 이집트 방산기업과 K9 자주포 부품 생산계약 체결 |url=http://www.theguru.co.kr/news/article.html?no=43937 |access-date=2022-12-02 |website=www.theguru.co.kr |language=ko}}</ref> In May 2023, despite the turmoil on Australian Land 8116 Phase 2, Hanwha Aerospace placed a significant order with Bisalloy Steels for Egyptian program.<ref>{{Cite web |author=<!--Not stated-->  |date=2023-05-16 |title=Hanwha places order with Bisalloy for Egyptian project |url=https://www.aumanufacturing.com.au/hanwha-places-order-with-bisalloy-for-egyptian-project |access-date=2023-05-20 |website=Australian Manufacturing Forum |language=en-AU}}</ref> At a military parade on 25 October 2023, the [[Egyptian Army]] unveiled the K9A1EGY in service with the 4th Armored Division.<ref name="Janes 2023-10-26">{{cite web|url=https://www.janes.com/defence-news/news-detail/egypt-displays-k9-howitzer-in-parade|title=Egypt displays K9 howitzer in parade|publisher=[[Janes Information Services]]|date=26 October 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231102053111/https://www.janes.com/defence-news/news-detail/egypt-displays-k9-howitzer-in-parade|archive-date=2 November 2023|access-date=2 November 2023|author=Jeremy Binnie}}</ref>

On 1 July 2024, media reported that the exact number of exports is 216 K9A1EGY, 39 K10, and 51 K11. Previously, Egypt received K9A1 and K10 vehicles with 1,000 horsepower Korean-made SMV1000 engines for testing purposes.<ref name="Egypt quantity">{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?feature=shared&v=6F9WlU7PDZE |script-title=ko:국산 파워팩 자주포 탑재 첫 수출 |date=2024-07-01 |last=MBC경남 NEWS |access-date=2024-08-29 |via=YouTube}}</ref>

On 5 October 2024, Arab Defense reported that the Ministry of Military Production announced local manufacturing of the SMV1000 engine by the state-owned Helwan Casting Company, also known as Military Factory 9. In addition, Egypt is working with Hanwha Aerospace in transferring manufacturing technology and installing production lines. The Military 200 will be the main manufacturer, and the Military 100 will produce the CN98 cannon and armored steel. Moreover, Egypt plans to become the regional center to export the K9 Thunder system to African and Arab countries, and the Minister of Military Production confirmed negotiations with a number of countries.<ref name="egypt engine">{{Cite web |date=2024-10-05 |title=Egypt produces the advanced Korean K9 Thunder engine locally |url=https://www.defense-arabic.com/2024/10/05/%d9%85%d8%b5%d8%b1-%d8%aa%d9%86%d8%aa%d8%ac-%d9%85%d8%ad%d8%b1%d9%83-%d8%a7%d9%84%d9%85%d8%af%d9%81%d8%b9-%d8%a7%d9%84%d9%83%d9%88%d8%b1%d9%8a-%d8%a7%d9%84%d9%85%d8%aa%d8%b7%d9%88%d8%b1-k9-thunder/ |website=Arab Defense}}</ref>

===Romania===
On 23 September 2022, Romanian Minister of National Defense [[Vasile Dîncu]] visited South Korea and signed a letter of intent to strengthen defense cooperation. On 26 September, Romanian media reported that the military was interested in purchasing K9 Thunder and K2 Black Panther.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-09-27 |script-title=ko:루마니아, 한국의 K9자주포와 K2흑표전차 구매 희망 |url=https://www.g-enews.com/article/Global-Biz/2022/09/2022092706410047136ed0c62d49_1 |access-date=2022-09-28 |website=[[Global Economic (newspaper)|Global Economic]] |trans-website=Global Economics |language=ko}}</ref> Besides the K9 howitzers, Romania also expressed interest in the [[K239 Chunmoo]] [[multiple rocket launcher]] and the [[K21]] [[infantry fighting vehicle]]. On 6 February 2023, [[Hanwha Aerospace]] and [[Romarm]] signed a memorandum of understanding for Romanian production of [[Smokeless powder|powders]], explosives and other ground military systems.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-02-06 |title=România - planuri mari privind achizițiile din Coreea de Sud. Obuziere K9, mașini de luptă și K239 Chunmoo, versiunea coreeană a HIMARS |url=https://www.defenseromania.ro/romania-planuri-mari-privind-achizitiile-din-coreea-de-sud-obuziere-k9-masini-de-lupta-si-k239-chunmoo-versiunea-coreeana-a-himars_620978.html |work=Defense Romania |language=ro}}</ref>

In July, it was reported that Romania planned to acquire 54 (3 systems of 18) K9 Thunders.<ref>{{Cite web |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->  |title=S-a discutat producția în România a unor componente ale obuzierelor K9 Thunder. România demarează achiziția de obuziere autopropulsate |url=https://www.defenseromania.ro/s-a-discutat-productia-in-romania-a-unor-componente-ale-obuzierelor-k9-thunder-romania-demareaza-achizitia-de-obuziere-autopropulsate_623475.html |access-date=2023-08-26 |website=Defense Romania |date=7 July 2023 |language=ro}}</ref> Romania also discussed the possibility of license producing some parts locally with Hanwha Aerospace.<ref>{{Cite web  |date=2023-07-09 |script-title=ko:한화 K9 자주포, 루마니아 수출 순풍... "1차분 8000억원" 전망도 |url=https://biz.chosun.com/industry/company/2023/07/10/V527FJ6RLNGTVCUHDRDKAMBGMM/ |access-date=2023-08-26 |website=[[ChosunBiz]] |language=ko}}</ref> One Romanian commentator, retired general Virgil Bălăceanu, argued that the K9 acquisition was part of a broader shift back to tracked and away from wheeled vehicles in military doctrine, motivated by the observed importance of all-terrain mobility in combat during the [[Russian invasion of Ukraine]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Curtifan |first=Tudor |date=2023-10-25 |title=România cumpără obuziere autopropulsate șenilate de 155 mm cu un motiv. De ce tehnica pe roți nu a fost un pariu câștigător |url=https://www.defenseromania.ro/romania-cumpara-obuziere-autopropulsate-senilate-de-155-mm-cu-un-motiv-de-ce-tehnica-pe-roti-nu-a-fost-un-pariu-castigator_625217.html |access-date=2024-02-04 |website=Defense Romania |language=ro}}</ref> A second stage of the program, however, includes the acquisition of two systems consisting of 18 wheeled howitzers each intended to equip the lighter ''[[Vânători de munte]]'' units.<ref>{{cite AV media|title=Podcasturile Observatorul militar, ep.31, invitat general-lt. dr. ing. Teodor Incicaș |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S6ky-0c8iYg |via=[[YouTube]] |publisher=Studioul Multimedia - Observatorul militar |language=ro |format=video |date=4 September 2023 |time=31:55}}</ref>

The contract bid for the tracked systems started on 29 July 2023, and three companies participated: [[BMC Otomotiv|BMC Savunma Sanayi]] with the T-155 Firtina, [[Krauss-Maffei Wegmann]] with the Panzerhaubitze 2000, and Hanwha with the K9 Thunder. Of the three participants, only Hanwha progressed to the second phase of the bid, which involved negotiations regarding the technical and financial proposal. The second phase was completed in April 2024, though no final contract was signed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://monitorulapararii.ro/sud-coreenii-de-la-hanwha-au-pus-ochii-pe-romania-vor-deschiderea-unui-centru-de-logistica-si-mentenanta-pentru-obuzierele-autopropulsate-k9-dar-1-54656|title=Sud coreenii de la Hanwha au pus ochii pe România. Vor deschiderea unui centru de logistică şi mentenanţă pentru obuzierele autopropulsate K9, dar planurile sunt mult mai mari. Partea I|language=ro|author=Andreea Soare|website=[[:ro:Monitorul Apărării și Securității]]|trans-website=Defence & Security Monitor|date=26 April 2024}}</ref>

On 19 June 2024, Romanian Defense Minister [[Angel Tîlvăr]] finally decided to introduce 54 K9s worth [[South Korean won|₩]]1.3 trillion ([[United States dollar|$]]920 million) during an official meeting with South Korean Defense Minister [[Shin Won-sik]], who is visiting Romania.<ref name="YNA 2024-06-19">{{cite web|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20240619007200315|title=Romania to buy S. Korean K-9 howitzers for US$920 mln|publisher=[[Yonhap News Agency]]|date=19 June 2024|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20240619135115/https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20240619007200315|archivedate=19 June 2024|accessdate=19 June 2024|author1=Lee Min-ji}}</ref> The Romanian version is called '''K9 Tunet''' and will have the "most modern technical specifications" of the K9 according to Peter Bae, the vice president of Hanwha Aerospace Europe.<ref name="monitorulapararii 2024-06-19">{{cite web |url=https://monitorulapararii.ro/romania-confirma-achizitia-obuzierelor-autopropulsate-k9-tunet-de-la-hanwha-aerospace-1-54929 |title=România confirmă achiziţia obuzierelor autopropulsate K9 Tunet de la Hanwha Aerospace |website=[[:ro:Monitorul Apărării și Securității]] |trans-website=Defence & Security Monitor |date=19 June 2024 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20240619160451/https://monitorulapararii.ro/romania-confirma-achizitia-obuzierelor-autopropulsate-k9-tunet-de-la-hanwha-aerospace-1-54929 |archive-date=19 June 2024 |access-date=19 June 2024 |last=Soare |first=Andreea}}</ref><ref name="defenseromania 2024-05-02">{{cite web |url=https://www.defenseromania.ro/ce-stim-despre-tunetul-romanesc-versiunea-obuzierelor-k9-pe-care-o-va-avea-romania-va-dispune-de-cele-mai-moderne-specificatii-tehnice_628113.html |title=Ce știm despre Tunetul românesc. Versiunea obuzierelor K9 pe care o va avea România va dispune de cele mai moderne specificații tehnice |publisher=Defense Romania |date=2 May 2024 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20240619160447/https://www.defenseromania.ro/ce-stim-despre-tunetul-romanesc-versiunea-obuzierelor-k9-pe-care-o-va-avea-romania-va-dispune-de-cele-mai-moderne-specificatii-tehnice_628113.html |archive-date=19 June 2024 |access-date=19 June 2024 |last=Curtifan |first=Tudor}}</ref> The first 18 vehicles will be completely built at the [[Changwon]] factory in Korea while the rest will be assembled in Romania.<ref name="tvrinfo 2024-06-19">{{cite web|url=https://tvrinfo.ro/armata-romana-cumpara-cateva-zeci-de-obuziere-senilate-k-9-tunet-din-coreea-de-sud/|title=Armata română cumpără câteva zeci de obuziere șenilate K-9 Tunet, din Coreea de Sud|publisher=[[Televiziunea Română]]|date=19 June 2024|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20240619180951/https://tvrinfo.ro/armata-romana-cumpara-cateva-zeci-de-obuziere-senilate-k-9-tunet-din-coreea-de-sud/|archivedate=19 June 2024|accessdate=19 June 2024|author1=}}</ref>

On 9 July 2024, Hanwha Aerospace signed the ₩1.3 trillion contract with the [[Ministry of National Defence (Romania)|Romanian Ministry of Defense]] to supply 54 K9s and 36 K10s, including ammunition and support equipment packages. Hanwha will deliver the vehicle from 2027 in cooperation with a local defense company in Romania.<ref name="Joongang Daily 2024-07-10">{{cite web|url=https://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/2024-07-10/national/defense/Korea-to-export-K9-howitzers-to-Romania-in-nearly-1-billion-deal/2087163|title=Korea to export K9 howitzers to Romania in nearly $1 billion deal|publisher=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]|date=10 July 2024|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20240711001150/https://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/2024-07-10/national/defense/Korea-to-export-K9-howitzers-to-Romania-in-nearly-1-billion-deal/2087163|archivedate=11 July 2024|accessdate=11 July 2024|author1=Seo Ji-eun|author2=Lee Hay-june}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-07-10 |title="10번째 K9 도입국 탄생"… 한화에어로스페이스, 루마니아와 1.4조 계약 |url=https://www.hanwhaaerospace.com/kor/media/newsroom/view.do?seq=417 |website=Hanwha Aerospace}}</ref>

Hanwha plans to build the local production factory in [[Petrești, Dâmbovița]] County. Named the Hanwha Armoured Vehicle Centre of Excellence (H-ACE) Europe, the facility will be the first of its kind in Europe. With an area of 180,000 m<sup>2</sup>, the factory will also feature testing facilities, a driving test track and advanced assembly lines. The construction began in February 2026.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.romania-insider.com/hanwha-aerospace-factory-romania-feb-2026|title=South Korea's Hanwha Aerospace begins construction of armored vehicle factory in Romania|website=romania-insider.com|date=12 February 2026}}</ref> Meanwhile, Hanwha will deliver 18 K9s and 12 K10s from South Korea by autumn 2026.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Hanwha to Open K9 Howitzer Factory in Romania |date=April 2025 |url=https://thedefensepost.com/2025/04/01/romania-hanwha-k9-factory/ |access-date=2025-06-30 |language=en-US}}</ref><ref name="ProTV2026"/> All vehicles will be delivered in three batches over a period of five years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediafax.ro/social/primul-obuzier-k9-tunetul-a-iesit-de-pe-linia-de-productie-pentru-fortele-terestre-romane-23712145|title=Primul obuzier K9 "Tunetul" a ieșit de pe linia de producție pentru Forțele Terestre Române|first=Gabriel|last=Pecheanu|language=ro|website=mediafax.ro|date=30 March 2026}}</ref>

===Vietnam===
The negotiation for K9 Thunder began when [[Nguyễn Xuân Phúc]], the president of Vietnam, visited South Korea for the 30th anniversary of diplomatic ties in 2022.

In March 2023, Vietnam's highest military figure [[Phan Văn Giang]] and other officials showed interests in the K9 by visiting [[Republic of Korea Army|ROKA]] K9 operator unit and had discussion with [[Hanwha Aerospace]] on the potential K9 procurement for VPA.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-03-28 |title=General Phan Van Giang visits RoK's artillery brigade |url=https://en.qdnd.vn/military/intl-relations-and-cooperation/general-phan-van-giang-visits-rok-s-artillery-brigade-550716 |website=[[People's Army Newspaper]] |quote=During the visit, General [[Phan Văn Giang|Phan Van Giang]] and his entourage watched a live-fire demonstration of K9A1 self-propelled howitzer and were briefed on the brigade's organization and its staffed weapons and equipment, including K9A1 self-propelled howitzers and K10 automatic ammunition resupply vehicles.}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web |title=Vietnam outlines intent to procure K9 howitzer |url=https://www.janes.com/defence-news/news-detail/vietnam-outlines-intent-to-procure-k9-howitzer |access-date=2024-04-25 |website=Janes.com |date=24 April 2024 |publisher=[[Janes Information Services]] |language=en |quote=Vietnamese Vice-Minister of National Defence Hoang Xuan Chien expressed an intention to procure the K9 at the '11th Korea-Vietnam Defense Strategy Dialogue' held in Hanoi on 23 April, according to a press release issued by the South Korea's Ministry of National Defense (MND) one day later.<br />Vietnam requires new artillery to replace its decades-old inventories including 155 mm M114 and 105 mm M101 howitzers. Reportedly, the People's Army of Vietnam seeks to procure 108 units of 155 mm howitzers.}}</ref>

In April 2024, it was reported that the [[Ministry of Defence (Vietnam)|Vietnam Ministry of National Defence]] has officially outlined the K9 procurement plan to its [[Ministry of National Defense (South Korea)|South Korean counterpart]], with Korean officials willingly support the deal. 108 units was mentioned as the potential number.<ref name=":1" />

On 27 July 2025, Hanwha Aerospace announced that 20 K9s will be delivered to [[KOTRA|Korea Trade-Investment Promotion Agency]] (KOTRA) as the program is signed between two governments, and all export processes for delivery of systems and vehicles will be carried out through intergovernmental transactions (G2G) through KOTRA. The amount of the contract is ₩351,758,967,000, which excludes [[Maintenance#Definitions|MRO]]. Vietnam confirmed the purchase on 11 August during [[Tô Lâm]]'s visit to South Korea.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-08-11 |title=베트남 가는 K-9 자주포… 공산국가·동남아 첫 수출 성과 |url=https://www.asiatoday.co.kr/kn/view.php?key=20250812010005305 |access-date=2025-08-12 |website=아시아투데이 |language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-08-11 |title=[단독]베트남 K-9자주포 도입 확정… 공산국가 첫 수출 |url=https://www.asiae.co.kr/article/2025081108430484254 |access-date=2025-08-11 |website=아시아경제 |language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://v.daum.net/v/20250811084911347 |title=[단독]베트남 K-9자주포 도입 확정… 공산국가 첫 수출|website=Daum News |language=ko |access-date=12 August 2025}}</ref>

===Failed bids===

====Denmark====
The K9 Thunder participated in a bid against Nexter Systems' [[CAESAR self-propelled howitzer#CAESAR 8x8|CAESAR 8x8]] and [[Soltam Systems]] [[ATMOS 2000]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.heraldcorp.com/view.php?ud=20161025000595 |title=韓ㆍ덴마크 정상회담, K-9 자주포 방산협력 논의 |publisher=[[Herald Corporation]] |date=2016-10-25}}</ref> In March 2017, the Danish military announced it had selected the competing CAESAR 8x8 instead.

In January 2023, Denmark requested Hanwha Aerospace, Nexter Systems, and [[Lockheed Martin]] to submit a proposal to fill up the gap created by the donation of entire fleet of CAESAR 8x8 to Ukraine, which Lockheed Martin refused by offering a high cost. However, Denmark leveraged the situation to make ongoing negotiations in favor of [[Elbit Systems]]. On 25 January, Denmark made an agreement with Elbit Systems to purchase ATMOS 2000 and [[PULS (multiple rocket launcher)|PULS]] (Precise and Universal Launching System), and signed the contract in March without notifying anything to Hanwha and Nexter despite Denmark being the requester.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dr.dk/nyheder/politik/dansk-agent-om-vaabenkoeb-jeg-forsoegte-forgaeves-aflevere-tilbud-om-genvej-til|title=Dansk agent om våbenkøb: Jeg forsøgte forgæves at aflevere tilbud om genvej til sydkoreanske kanoner|publisher=[[DR (broadcaster)|Danish Broadcasting Corporation]]|date=11 August 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230811053029/https://www.dr.dk/nyheder/politik/dansk-agent-om-vaabenkoeb-jeg-forsoegte-forgaeves-aflevere-tilbud-om-genvej-til|archive-date=11 August 2023|access-date=11 August 2023|author1=Mads Korsager Nielsen |author2=Mette Pabst}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-08-10 |script-title=ko:우크라이나 무기 지원한 덴마크, 한화 K9 자주포 구애 |url=http://www.theguru.co.kr/news/article.html?no=58274 |access-date=2023-08-26 |website=www.theguru.co.kr |language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-08-11 |script-title=ko:덴마크 국방장관, 이스라엘 무기 도입 공식사과...한화 K9 자주포 다시 기회 |url=http://www.theguru.co.kr/news/article.html?no=58302 |access-date=2023-08-26 |website=www.theguru.co.kr |language=ko}}</ref>

====United Arab Emirates====
The UAE failed to acquire K9s due to German arms restrictions on the use of the MT 881 Ka-500 diesel engines, according to a South Korean MOFA official.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://independent.ng/uae-k9-howitzer-acquisition-frozen-under-arms-embargo/ |location=Lagos, Nigeria| title=UAE K9 Howitzer Acquisition Frozen Under Arms Embargo – Independent Newspaper Nigeria | date=9 July 2020 |newspaper=[[Independent (Nigeria)|Independent]]}}</ref>

====United Kingdom====
In September 2021, Hanwha Defense launched Team Thunder joined by [[Leonardo S.p.A.|Leonardo UK]] (navigation, FCS, electronics), [[Pearson plc|Pearson Engineering]] (manufacturing), Horstman (suspension), and Soucy Defense (track) to participate in the Mobile Fires Platform (MFP) program, starting in late 2023 to replace Britain's [[AS90]] with a K9A2 variant.<ref name="UK MFP">{{cite news|url=https://www.defensenews.com/industry/2021/06/02/skoreas-hanwha-pitches-k9-howitzer-for-british-mobile-fires-program/ |title=SKorea's Hanwha pitches K9 howitzer for British mobile fires program |publisher=Defense News |date=2021-06-02}}</ref> The team expanded as Lockheed Martin UK (turret & autoloader) joined Team Thunder in March 2022.<ref>{{Cite web  |date=2022-03-23 |script-title=ko:한화디펜스, K9 자주포 영국 수출 위한 '팀 썬더' 협력 확대 |url=https://biz.chosun.com/industry/company/2022/03/23/ELZM4FZU55EUTM72CHLHV3DUAM/ |access-date=2022-06-05 |website=[[ChosunBiz]] |language=ko}}</ref> The K9A2 was first revealed in the United Kingdom during Defense Vehicle Dynamics 2022 at UTAC [[Millbrook Proving Ground]] in September 2022.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-09-22 |script-title=ko:한화디펜스, 영국서 최신형 K9자주포 공개 |url=https://www.g-enews.com/article/Industry/2022/09/2022092216595167814fb262fcb_1 |access-date=2022-09-28 |website=[[Global Economic (newspaper)|Global Economic]] |language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |title=K9A2 Self-Propelled Howitzer at Millbrook Proving Ground, UK | date=23 September 2022 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oD19fa1viTk |language=en |access-date=2022-09-28}}</ref><ref name="K9 UK partners interview">{{Citation |script-title=ko:록히드마틴이 K9 자주포를 만든다? '팀 썬더' 영국 현지 취재! 레오나르도, 피어슨 엔지니어링, 수시 디펜스! 다 보고 왔습니다! l K-방산 팩트체크 6편 [프파S] | date=15 November 2022 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O55lkhLjkQ0 |language=en |access-date=2022-12-05}}</ref>

In March 2023, the United Kingdom purchased 14 [[Archer Artillery System|Archers]] from Swedish inventory to fill the gap after transferring 32 AS90s to Ukraine. Archer is one of the competitors of the MFP.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Chuter |first=Andrew |date=2023-03-16 |title=British Army buys 14 Archer howitzers to fill gap left by Ukraine aid |url=https://www.defensenews.com/land/2023/03/16/british-army-buys-14-archer-howitzers-to-fill-gap-left-by-ukraine-aid/ |access-date=2023-05-15 |website=Defense News |language=en}}</ref>

[[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|British Ministry of Defense]] requested the Team Thunder to conduct tests on CRT with K9A2 technology demonstrator.<ref>{{Cite web |last=tf.co.kr |date=2023-07-08 |script-title=ko:한화에어로, '복합 고무궤도 장착' K9 자주포 시험 주행...게임체인저될까? |url=https://news.tf.co.kr/read/ptoday/2029245.htm |access-date=2023-08-26 |website=더팩트 |language=ko}}</ref>

On 24 April 2024, the UK announced its selection of the [[RCH 155]] for the British Army's Mobile Fires Platform programme, as a successor for the [[AS-90]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Chuter |first=Andrew |date=2023-12-11 |title=Babcock, Rheinmetall UK join BAE push for British Army's howitzer |url=https://www.defensenews.com/global/europe/2023/12/11/babcock-rheinmetall-uk-join-bae-push-for-british-armys-howitzer/ |access-date=2024-03-18 |website=Defense News |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Britain to purchase Boxer-based RCH155 artillery systems |url=https://ukdefencejournal.org.uk/britain-to-purchase-boxer-based-rch155-artillery-systems/ |access-date=24 April 2024 |work=[[UK Defence Journal]] |date=24 April 2024}}</ref> The vehicles will be built in both Germany and the UK with over 100 UK-based suppliers manufacturing components.<ref>{{cite news |title=PM: UK and Germany open 'new chapter' in defence partnership |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/pm-uk-and-germany-open-new-chapter-in-defence-partnership |access-date=24 April 2024 |work=[[GOV.UK]] |date=24 April 2024}}</ref> The platform will consist of the Remote-Controlled Howitzer 155mm (RCH 155) weapon module fitted to the rear half of the [[Boxer (armoured fighting vehicle)|Boxer]] mechanised infantry vehicle (MIV) and will be in service with the [[Royal Artillery]] by the end of the decade.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Thomas |first=Richard |date=2024-04-24 |title=German RCH 155 artillery selected for British Army's Mobile Fires Platform |url=https://www.army-technology.com/news/german-rch-155-artillery-selected-for-british-armys-mobile-fires-platform/ |access-date=2024-04-24 |website=Army Technology |language=en-US}}</ref>

==Variants and upgrades==
* '''XK9:''' experimental prototype. 2 built
* '''K9 Thunder:''' the first-production variant for the [[Republic of Korea Armed Forces]]
** '''[[T-155 Firtina]] (Storm):''' Turkish variant of the K9. Manufactured by [[Turkish Land Forces]] with subsystems from South Korea. The turret is modified to store 30 ammunition instead of 32 while increasing hull stored ammunition from 16 to 18.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Toper |first=Ezgi |title=What you need to know about Türkiye's self-propelled Firtina II howitzers |url=https://www.trtworld.com/turkey/Ezgi%20Toper |access-date=2023-05-21 |website=What you need to know about Türkiye's self-propelled Firtina II howitzers |language=en }}{{Dead link|date=July 2023 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The vehicle has APU installed, but lacks panoramic scope for manual firing
*** '''Gürhan:''' hybrid engine test vehicle of the T-155
*** '''T-155 Firtina 2''': Turkish upgrade of the T-155 Firtina
* '''K9 PIP (Product Improvement Program)''': K9 upgrade plan by South Korea, noticeably adding APU and better FCS. The upgrade later evolved to the K9A1 with more modifications.
** '''AS9 "Aussie Thunder":''' offered Australian variant for the LAND 17 program. It featured enhanced FCS, BMS-F, RWS, anti-tank mine protection, and suspension upgrade to support increased weight.
** '''PK9:''' a modified K9 chassis used to produce Polish [[AHS Krab]] self-propelled howitzer. License produced by [[Huta Stalowa Wola]].
** '''K9 Vajra-T (Lightning):''' Indian variant of the K9. Manufactured by [[Larsen & Toubro]] under license with 50% Indian components. It is customized for desert and alpine operations, and is the first variant to equip [[Safran]] MINEO DFSS, a dedicated gunner's sight for direct firing capability similar to main battle tanks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/army-inducts-new-artillery-guns-after-three-decades/article25452662.ece|title=Army fire power gets booster shot|last=Peri|first=Dinakar|date=2018-11-09|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-01-20|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref name="MINEO DFSS">{{Cite web |date=2022-10-05 |script-title=ko:한화 '호주 자주포 사업'에 프랑스 사프란 가세 |url=http://www.theguru.co.kr/news/article.html?no=43116 |access-date=2022-12-02 |website=www.theguru.co.kr |language=ko}}</ref>
** '''K9FIN Moukari (Sledge-hammer):''' Finnish variant of the K9 transferred from the Republic of Korea Army inventory after overhaul and upgrades. Finnish modifications were performed by Millog.
** '''K9EST Kõu (Thunder):''' Estonian variant of the K9 transferred from the Republic of Korea Army inventory after overhaul and upgrades. Estonian modifications were performed by Go Craft.
** '''K9A1:''' First enhanced variant for the Republic of Korea Armed Forces, and is in service since 2018. All K9s operated by South Korea will be upgraded to A1 or future variant by 2030.
*** '''K9 VIDAR (versatile indirect artillery system) (Batch I):''' Norwegian variant of the K9A1 with Norwegian subsystems and increased protection by installing spall liner. Uses Safran MINEO DFSS for direct firing.<ref name="MINEO DFSS"/>
**** '''K9 VIDAR (Batch II):''' second production batch of the K9 VIDAR. It has visible changes such as driver's optics.
**** '''AS9 Huntsman:''' Australian variant of the K9 VIDAR with additional armor package and enhanced suspension. New hull design is similar to the [[K21#Future development|AS21 Redback]].<ref name="AS9">{{cite news| url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/special-reports/huntsman-howitzers-action-ready-by-2023/news-story/b1e22c946f436d76586641b41e06792c |title=Huntsman howitzers action ready by 2023 |publisher=The Weekend Australian |date=2021-06-01}}</ref>
***** '''K9 Tunet:''' Romanian variant, will feature the "most modern technical specifications" of the K9. No further information available.<ref name="defenseromania 2024-05-02" />
*** '''K9A1EGY:''' Egyptian variant of the K9A1. Will be produced under license in Egypt.
*** '''K9PL (Batch I):''' Polish variant of the K9A1. Equipped with the Polish network system and fire control system. First 48 secondhand vehicles are known as '''K9GF'''.
**** '''K9PL (Batch II):''' enhanced variant of the Batch I with 13 additional systems.<ref name="K9GF"/>
* '''K9A2:''' second enhanced variant for the Republic of Korea Armed Forces. 1 prototype built and shown to the public in 2022, and is in development. Also known as K9A2 Block-I to differentiate from 58 caliber variant.
** '''K9A2 Block-II:''' 155&nbsp;mm 58 caliber variant of K9A2. Proposal stage only.
* '''K9A3:''' fully automated and unmanned K9A2. Under development.<ref name="salesperson interview" />
<hr/>
* '''[[K10 ammunition resupply vehicle|K10 ARV]] (ammunition resupply vehicle):''' automatic resupplying vehicle for the K9 based on the same platform
** '''K10 VIDAR (versatile indirect artillery system):''' Norwegian variant of the K10
** '''K10EGY''': Egyptian variant of the K10
** '''K10 AARV (armored ammunition resupply vehicle):''' enhanced protection variant of the K10 ARV
*** '''AS10:''' Australian variant of the K10 AARV – similar configuration to the AS9<ref name="AS9" />
*** '''AS10C2:''' suggested protected command & control post variant based on the AS10
<hr/>
* '''K11 FDCV (fire direction control vehicle):''' fire direction control vehicle based on the K10
** '''K11EGY''': Egyptian variant of the K11 with anti-ship mission capability added
* '''K11A1''': enhanced variant of the K11. It remotely operates up to three K9A3 howitzers and is armed with the RCWS, anti-air missile launchers, and additional armor plate for mine protection.

==Operators==
[[File:K9 operators.svg|thumb|400px|A map of operators of the K9 Thunder or its variants]]

===Current operators===
{{flag|Australia}} – 2 '''AS9 Huntsman''' and 1 '''AS10 AARV''' delivered as of January 2025.
